# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: azerbaijani-alphabet
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/a-cyrillic] The Cyrillic letter А was derived directly from the Greek letter Alpha (Α α).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/a-cyrillic] In the Early Cyrillic alphabet its name was азъ (azǔ), meaning the personal pronoun "I".
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/a-cyrillic] In the Cyrillic numeral system, the Cyrillic letter А has a value of 1.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/a-cyrillic] Throughout history, the Cyrillic letter А has had various shapes, but today is standardized on one that looks exactly like the Latin letter A, including the italic and lower case forms.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/a-cyrillic] In most languages that use the Cyrillic alphabet – such as Bulgarian, Ukrainian, Belarusian, Russian, Rusyn, Serbian, Macedonian and Montenegrin – the Cyrillic letter А represents the open central unrounded vowel /a/.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/a-cyrillic] In Ingush and Chechen, the Cyrillic letter А represents both the open back unrounded vowel /ɑ/ when stressed and the mid-central vowel /ə/ when unstressed.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/a-cyrillic] In Turkic languages that use the Cyrillic script it represents the open back unrounded vowel /ɑ/, with the exception of Volga Tatar, in which it represents the open back rounded vowel /ɒ/, and Uzbek, in which it represents the near-open front unrounded vowel /æ/.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/a-cyrillic] In languages that contrast vowel length the letter can be written as double vowel.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] The current **Abkhaz alphabet** is a modified variant of the Cyrillic script used for the Abkhaz language.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] Abkhaz was not a written language until the 19th century.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] Until then, Abkhazians—especially elites—had been using Greek (until c.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] 9th century), Georgian (9–19th centuries), and partially Turkish (18th century).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] The first Abkhaz alphabet was created in 1862 by Peter von Uslar.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] It had 55 letters and was based on the Cyrillic script.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] Another version, having 51 letters, was used in 1892 by Dimitry Gulia and K.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] In 1909, the alphabet was again expanded to 55 letters by Andria Tchotchua to adjust to the extensive consonantal inventory of Abkhaz.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] In 1926, during the *korenizatsiya* policy in the Soviet Union, the Cyrillic alphabet was replaced by a Latin alphabet devised by Nikolay Marr.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] It featured 76 letters and was called the "Abkhaz analytical alphabet".
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] In 1928, this was replaced by another Latin alphabet.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] From 1938 to 1954 the Abkhaz language was written in Georgian *Mkhedruli script*.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] Since 1954, the Abkhaz language has been written in a new 58-letter (now 64-letter) Cyrillic alphabet (see chart below).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] Of these, 38 are graphically distinct; the rest are digraphs with ⟨ь⟩ and ⟨ә⟩ which indicate palatalization and labialization, respectively.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] In 1996, the most recent reform of the alphabet was implemented: while labialization had hitherto been marked with two additional letters, ә and у (у was used in the digraphs гу, ҕу, ку, қу, ҟу, and ху, which were not considered separate letters), since then only ә was retained in this function.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] Unusually, the Cyrillic plosive letters к п т represent ejective consonants; the non-ejectives (pulmonic consonants) are derived from these by means of a descender at the bottom of the letter.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] In the case of the affricates, however, the plain letters are pulmonic, and the derived letters ejective.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] The modern Abkhaz orthography gives preference to the letters г к п т х ч with descender (ӷ қ ԥ ҭ ҳ ҷ).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] The letters (ҕ ҧ) had previously (before 1996) had a hook, which ҕ still does in Yakut.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] In pre-Soviet alphabets the hook was also used in ӄ ꚋ, see above.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] The letters ь and ә are used as parts of digraphs, but are listed separately in the alphabet.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] Besides the digraphs listed in the alphabet, the letter ь occurs in ль /lʲ/, which is used in some loanwords.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] Letters or digraphs in brackets are not part of the alphabet.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/abkhaz-alphabet] Letters without a modern equivalent represent phonemes only present in the Bzyb dialect, as the literary standard dialect switched from Bzyb to Abzhywa.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Adamawa Fulfulde was originally brought to Cameroon in the early parts of the 19th century during a religious war (Jihad) that was launched by Usman dan Fodio from Northern Nigeria.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] It is an Atlantic language that belongs to the Niger–Congo language family.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] The speakers of the language are the Fulani people.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] The language itself is divided into a number of sub-dialects: Maroua, Garoua, Ngaondéré, Kambariire, Mbororoore, and Bilkire.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] In Sudan, the language is spoken mainly in Blue Nile, Gedaref, and Sennar states with some communities of speakers also found in North Kordofan and South Kordofan states.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] In South Sudan, it is spoken in Western Bahr el Ghazal state by Ambororo cattle herders.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] In Chad, it is spoken in Lac Léré Department in the Mayo-Kebbi Ouest Region.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] In Nigeria, it is spoken in Adamawa and Taraba states.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] While in Cameroon the language is widespread across the Far North and Northern regions of the country.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] The word order for Adamawa Fulfulde is SOV (subject–object–verb).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Adamawa Fulfulde is mostly written in a modified Arabic script, in the tradition of Ajami script, that it shares with many other languages such as Hausa language, and many other languages in Sub-Sahara Africa.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Writing Fulfulde with Arabic script has a long tradition and old manuscripts are found in all of West Africa.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Latin alphabet is also used for writing of Adamawa.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] The usage of Latin is a lot more recent, only coming to existence with the arrival of European Christian.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Still, in Cameroon, Arabic alphabet remains more popular for writing of Adamawa Fulfulde than Latin.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] The Adamawa Fulfulde Ajami alphabet is the result of many decades of efforts to standardize, starting from the 1960s.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] By the 1990s, the orthography was well established.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] In 1998, at the JCMWA/MICCAO conference in Ngaoundéré, Cameroon, over 100 representatives from 14 West African countries agreed that this orthography would be a good standard for writing the Fulfulde language with Arabic script.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] The alphabet consists of 33 basic letters, 28 plus *hamaza* from Arabic, and 4 are new letters created for use in Fulfulde.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] 10 of the Arabic letters are only used for writing Arabic loanwords, and have no use for writing indigenous Fulfulde words.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] This letter does come in the beginning of words as a vowel diacritic carrier for common Arabic loanwords.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Character unique to Fulfulde, not found in Arabic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Pronounced as [θ] in Arabic, but as [s] in Fulfulde.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] This letter is pronounced as [h] in Fulfulde, and is used for representing the sound [h] (except in Arabic loanwords).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] The latter is only used in Arabic loanwords in Fulfulde.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Pronounced as [x] in Arabic, but as [h] or [x] in Fulfulde.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] This letter has a variation of pronunciations in different local dialects.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Pronounced as [sˤ] in Arabic, but as [s] in Fulfulde.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Pronounced as [dˤ] in Arabic, but as [d] in Fulfulde.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] This is the local indigenous innovation in the Adamawa dialectical area.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Pronounced as [q] in Arabic, but as [k~g] in Fulfulde.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] , in which case it will not carry any diacritic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] This letter serves two functions, either as a consonant [w], or it lengthens vowels [o] or [u].
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] This letter serves two functions, either as a consonant [j], or it lengthens vowel [i].
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Letter used for lengthening of vowel [e].
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] In Adamawa Fulfulde, there are 4 prenasalized consonants.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Prenasalized consonants are written as a digraph (combination of two consonants).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] The first letter of the digraph representing a prenasalized consonant cannot take any diacritic, including zero-vowel diacritic *sukun* '◌ْ‎'.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Like other languages that have historically been written within what's known as the Ajami tradition, there is a full relaince on diacritics for writing vowels.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] In Arabic there are only three diacritics, which represent [a] '◌َ‎', [u] [i] '◌ُ‎', and [i] '◌ِ‎'.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] The general tradition is that when there are vowels that don't exist in Arabic, new diacritics are created.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] In Adamawa Fulfulde these include the Quranic imāla '◌ٜ‎' for vowel [e], and a special diacritic '◌ٛ‎' for vowel [o].
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Unlike Arabic orthography, or other Arabic-derived scripts, in Ajami tradition, all diacritics are written.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Even letters that don't have any vowels, are written with a *zero-vowel/sukun* '◌ْ‎' diacritic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Vowels are lengthened by combining the diacritic with a follow-up letter, just as is the tradition in Arabic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] These follow-up letters are written without a diacritic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] ' can be part of a digraph representing prenasalized consonants.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] In these instances, these two letters are written without a diacritic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Adyghe is closely related to the Kabardian or East Circassian language; some reject the distinction between the two languages in favour of both being dialects of a unitary Circassian language, others argue they are closely related but technically distinct languages.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Despite phonological differences, Circassian languages are reciprocally intelligible, with speakers being able to communicate with varying degrees of efficiency.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] While the self-designation for both Adyghe and Kabardian language is *Adyghe*, in linguistic and administrative terms, "Adyghe" refers specifically to the language of the western tribes of Circassians, while "Kabardian" refers to the language of the two eastern tribes (Kabardians and Besleney).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Ubykh, Abkhaz and Abaza are more distantly related to Adyghe.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Adyghe is also known as West Circassian or Lower Circassian.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Adyghe belongs to the Northwest Caucasian language family.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Glottochronological studies suggest that the common Proto-Northwest Caucasian language split into the Circassian, Abkhaz, and Ubykh branches roughly 5,000 years ago.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] One of the earliest attempts to create a standard for the Adyghe language was made by Natouko Sheretluk (Natouko Efendi), a Shapsug nobleman.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] He opened a madrasa in his native village of Bogundyr and compiled an Adyghe alphabet and grammar.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Leonty Lyulye, a Russian official who lived for many years among the Shapsugs, Natukhays, and Abadzekhs on the Black Sea coast, published a "Russian-Circassian Dictionary" and a brief grammar in Odessa in 1846.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Lyulye identified three dialects of Adyghe: "Kabardian", "Besleney", and a third he called "Common Circassian" (referring to the Western coastal dialects).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] He tried to base his dictionary on this "Common" dialect.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Another pre-Soviet attempt was made by Wumar Bersey, an Abzakh.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] On March 14, 1853, he published the "Primer of the Circassian Language" (Adyghe Alphabet) in Tiflis (Tbilisi), based on the Arabic script.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] This date (March 14) is now celebrated annually as the "Day of the Adyghe Language".
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] The standard register of Adyghe, known as Literary Adyghe (Adyghe: Литературабз, lit.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] 'Literature language'), was created by Circassian linguist Daut Ashkhamaf based largely on the Chemguy dialect, which was chosen for its simplicity.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] However, Literary Adyghe is a constructed dialect and is distinct from the natural Chemguy dialect, as there was significant input from the dialects of other tribes who remained in the Caucasus after the Circassian exile, spesifically the Bzhedug, Shapsug, and partly Abzakh.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] In the 1930s, Ashkhamaf even utilized the term "Bzhedug-Temirgoy dialect" to describe the basis of the literary language.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] He argued that through the development of the literary language, these dialects were merging.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] In some cases, literary dialect preferred words from other dialects over Chemguy words, such as Bzhedug "ӏэ" (hand) and "тхьэ" (god) instead of the Chemguy "ӏа" and "тхьа", as well as specific ordinal numbers and verb forms.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Thus, being supra-dialectal, literary Adyghe stands in contrast to territorial dialects and serves as the unifying literary form of the language for speakers of diverse dialects.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] There were proposals to merge Adyghe and Kabardian to create a single Circassian literary language.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Another proposal was to select one of the two to serve as the single literary language for all Circassians.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] A rejected proposal by Circassian scholars argued for recognizing Kabardian as the sole literary language for all Circassians, as it had the most speakers.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] There were attempts to create a single unified alphabet for Adyghe, Kabardian, Chechen and Karachay-Balkar; but efforts failed because the leaders of the movement were accused of being "bourgeois nationalists" and executed in 1937.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Naloev, who was involved in the creation of the Kabardian alphabet, was executed by firing squad for alleged treason; he was rehabilitated posthumously in 1957.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Bolsheviks supported the creation of separate alphabets and grammars for the "Kyakh" (Western; the modern Adyghe language) and Kabardian, despite ongoing debates on unifying them.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Thus, Adyghe and Kabardian speakers could communicate easier orally as opposed to in writing due to different graphical representations and spelling rules.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] A more moderate proposal developed by the linguist M.A.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Kumakhov aimed to unify the alphabets and orthography without forcing a complete merger of spoken Adyghe and Kabardian.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] This project proposed standardizing the representation of identical phonemes (using the same letter for the same sound where they currently differ, such as the Adyghe `жъ`vs.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] The project was accepted by specialists at regional conferences in Nalchik and Maikop in 1998 and 1999.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] While the Parliament of the Kabardino-Balkarian Republic approved the project, the Parliament of the Republic of Adygea did not proceed to discuss it.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Cherkess) was a result of Soviet "ethnic engineering".
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] The International Circassian Association (ICA) officially stated the goal of creating a "uniform Circassian language" in its 2015 congress resolution.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] There are many books written in or translated into Adyghe. А significant milestone was the publication of the "ABC-book of the Circassian language" by Wumar Bersey in Tbilisi on March 14, 1853, a date now celebrated as the Day of the Adyghe Language and Writing.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] In the early 20th century, reformist movements in Baksan led to the publication of religious and ethical textbooks such as "The History of Islam" (Мыслъымэн Тхыдэ) in 1918.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] A popular Adyghe translation of the Quran was made by Koshbaye Pshimaf Iskhak Mashbash.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] The New Testament and many books of the Old Testament have been published in Adyghe by the Institute for Bible Translation in Moscow.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] In 2020 a bilingual edition of Ecclesiastes was released in Adyghe and Kabardian.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] In 1908, Circassian Union and Charity Society in Istanbul began printing Adyghe language texts in the newspaper *Ghuaze.* Following this, the "*Adığe-Gazete"* (Adyghe Newspaper) was introduced in 1919.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] In 1920, the bulletin "Diyane" was published in Istanbul using a Latin-based Adyghe alphabet.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] In the Middle East, a Circassian cultural society established in 1927 in El-Quneitra, Syria, published the newspaper "Mardzh" (Voice) from 1928 to 1932.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Adyghe Maq is the main Adyghe language newspaper in Russia.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] It is published in the capital of the Adyghe Republic, Maykop, five times a week.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] The newspaper *"*Socialist Adygea" started in Krasnodar in 1926 and relocated to Maikop ten years later. he Adigean branch of the Union of Soviet Writers launched the literary almanac "Friendship" in Maikop in 1946.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] For younger readers, the children's magazine *"*Constellation" is published in the Adyghe language.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Other early newspapers included *Qerehetlıq* (Black People) in 1924 and *Adığe Psevuç* (Adyghe Life) in 1926.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] According to the UNESCO 2009 map entitled "UNESCO Map of the World's Languages in Danger", the status of the Adyghe language in 2009, along with all its dialects (Adyghe, Western Circassian tribes; and Kabard-Cherkess, Eastern Circassian tribes), is classified as vulnerable.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Adyghe exhibits between 50 and 60 consonants depending on the dialect.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] All dialects possess a contrast between plain and labialized glottal stops.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] A very unusual minimal contrast, and possibly unique to the Abzakh dialect of Adyghe, is a three-way contrast between plain, labialized and palatalized glottal stops (although a palatalized glottal stop is also found in Hausa and a labialized one in Tlingit).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Shapsug (Black Sea) dialect of Adyghe contains a very uncommon sound: a voiceless bidental fricative [h̪͆], which corresponds to the voiceless velar fricative [x] found in other varieties of Adyghe.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] This sound is only known to be used in the Black Sea dialect.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] In the Black Sea coast Adyghe dialects (e.g.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Shapsug dialect and Natukhai dialect) there exist a palatalized voiced velar stop [ɡʲ], a palatalized voiceless velar stop [kʲ] and a palatalized velar ejective [kʲʼ] that were merged with [d͡ʒ], [t͡ʃ] and [t͡ʃʼ] in most Adyghe dialects.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] For example the Shapsug words "гьанэ" [ɡʲaːna] "shirt", "кьэт" [kʲat] "chicken" and "кӏьапсэ" [kʲʼaːpsa] "rope" are pronounced in other dialects as "джанэ" [d͡ʒaːna], "чэт" [t͡ʃat] and кӏапсэ [t͡ʃʼaːpsa].
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] In contrast to its large inventory of consonants, Adyghe has only three phonemic vowels in a vertical vowel system.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Adyghe alphabet contains some inconsistencies between visual representation and pronunciation which can be a point of confusion for learners.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] It is tempting to read the Circassian alphabet letters phonologically, but this is not always accurate.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] These letters are not part of the official alphabet, but they may appear in books that showcase the different dialects.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] For most of its history, Adyghe was an oral language.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] The folklore, particularly the Nart sagas, served as a repository for the language.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Widespread literacy in Adyghe did not exist until the modern era and literacy was limited to a few people.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] From the 6th–5th centuries BC until the first half of the 15th century, the Adyghe people used the Greek alphabet, initially introduced through ancient Greek colonies and later reinforced by the Byzantine Empire and the Christian church.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Early forms of the Cyrillic alphabet were also used during this period due to Russian influence.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] During the 13th to 15th centuries, the development of relations with the Genoese Republic led to some use of the Italian (Latin) script.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] In the 14th century, along with Islam, the Arabic script was adopted for Adyghe.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] It was referred to as Ajam**,** a writing system for the native language based on the Perso-Arabic script.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Since Adyghe has many more consonants than Arabic, the Ajam system required adding special diacritical marks or inventing new letters to represent sounds.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Early attempts to write Adyghe in modern Cyrillic started as early as 1829 and were followed by similar attempts.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] In 1853, the Adyghe educator Umar Bersey published the first "Primer of the Circassian Language" based on the Arabic script.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Over the following decades, several authors attempted to further improve the Adyghe Arabic orthography.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] The most successful attempt was the alphabet created by Akhmetov Bekukh.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] In this version, letters were designated for vowel sounds, and the orthography was transformed from an "Impure abjads to a true alphabet.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] In 1918, on the initiative of the Kuban Revolutionary Committee, a primer was published in Yekaterinodar.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] This official endorsement resulted in a literary boom in Adyghe and the publication of various newspapers, textbooks and other literature, including the *Adyghe Maq*, the main Adyghe language newspaper established in 1923.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] During the abovementioned decades, parallel with this process, the Perso-Arabic orthography had also been standardized for the sister Circassian language of Kabardian.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Although very similar in many aspects, there were minor variations, in which letters were included based on each respective phonology, and there were minor differences in presentation of a few consonants as well.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Arabic script was used until 1927, when as a part of the Soviet "Latinisation" campaign, a Latin-based alphabet was adopted.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Yakovlev and the Adyghe scholar Daud Ashkhamaf.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] In the late 1930s, the script was converted to Cyrillic to align with Russian.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] In the diaspora, a new Latin alphabet based on the Turkish alphabet was designed to better facilitate Adyghe and Kabardian education in Turkey, named the ABX alphabet.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Adyghe, like all Northwest Caucasian languages, has a basic subject–object–verb typology and is characterised by the ergative construction of sentences.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Turkey hosts the largest Circassian population, but the language lacks any legal recognition.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] However, after the collapse of the Ottoman Empire and the establishment of the modern republic, these schools were banned by the Kemalists.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Following the "Citizen, Speak Turkish!" campaign and the closure of Circassian schools, the language was confined to the home.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] In educational settings, speaking Adyghe was strictly banned.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Students faced physical punishment and psychological alienation for speaking Adyghe, including during recess and outside of school grounds.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] To enforce this, teachers formed "discipline committees" made up of student informants.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Publishing in the language also faced state pressure; cultural magazines had to remove Circassian lyrics from traditional songs and publish only the musical notes to avoid government retribution.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Consequently, while the older generation retains fluency, proficiency among those under 50 is significantly diminished.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] In a study, Nusret Baş (Бажь Нусрэт), the then-president of the Federation of Circassian Associations, estimated that about 5% of Circassians in Turkey (including people of Circassian descent) speak their native language fluently.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Linguistically, the Adyghe spoken in Turkey exhibits distinct features as it was not subject to the standartisation policies in the Caucasus.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] It contains archaic vocabulary lost in the Caucasus, alongside Turkish loanwords.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] While the Chemguy dialect forms the basis of the literary language in the Republic of Adygea, the majority of the diaspora in Turkey speaks the Abzakh and Shapsug dialects (as well as Kabardian), alongside smaller numbers of Bzhedug and Hatuqay speakers.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Hatuqay dialect is spoken only in Turkey.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] In some cases, the physical mixing of different tribes led to dialectal convergence.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Frequent intermarriages between dialect groups led to the use of a mixed Adyghe koine or the dominance of one dialect in multi-tribal areas.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] In some cases, the boundaries between dialects became blurred, resulting in a hybrid oral communication style, sometimes even including hybrids with Kabardian or Abaza.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Due to assimilation, Adyghe speakers in Turkey sometimes use Turkish terms for numbers, days of the week, months, and colors.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Significant changes occurred following Turkey's European Union accession process in the early 2000s.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] The language policy was liberalized, which prompted revival efforts.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] In 2012, the Ministry of National Education introduced "Living Languages and Dialects" as an elective course for secondary schools, allowing Adyghe to be taught in public schools.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Classes are only opened if a set minimum number of students apply, and bureaucratic hurdles regarding application windows often hinder access to these classes.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Teachers are subject teachers with basic language skills rather than trained philologists, and they receive limited training in language pedagogy.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Educational materials are imported from Adygea and are designed for native speakers, making them difficult to adapt for diaspora students who are learning Adyghe as a second language.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] During the COVID-19 pandemic, transnational online courses were organized in collaboration with institutions in Russia, allowing students in Turkey, Jordan, and Germany to be taught by teachers directly from the Caucasus.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Düzce University has a Department of Caucasian Languages and Cultures, which offers "Circassian Language and Culture" programs, including the teaching of Adyghe in Cyrillic, as the surrounding region is inhabited largely by Shapsug and Abzakh Circassians.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Boğaziçi University began offering elective Adyghe courses in 2013.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] A significant debate persists in the Turkish diaspora regarding orthography of Adyghe.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Federation of Caucasian Associations (KAFFED) adopted the Cyrillic alphabet in 2004 to maintain continuity with the homeland, but other groups advocate for a Latin-based script to facilitate easier learning for Turkish speakers.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] This dispute intensified significantly when the Turkish Ministry of Education approved a Latin-based alphabet, called the ABX Latin Alphabet, for elective Circassian language courses in public schools, effectively creating a dual-alphabet system alongside the existing Cyrillic curriculum.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] KAFFED vehemently opposed this decision, arguing that it creates confusion and severs cultural ties with the autonomous republics in the Caucasus.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Demonstrations were at Ministry of Education offices across the country with slogans including "Hands off my alphabet," "We want our mother tongue's alphabet" and "How does Arabic in Latin letters sound?".
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Ubykh people in Turkey, who originally possessed their own distinct language, largely integrated with the Adyghe during their exile and adopted the Adyghe language as their own.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Ubykh language went extinct in 1992; today Ubykh people speak Adyghe or Turkish.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Adyghe State University is working to document Adyghe language and folklore in Turkey.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Circassian community in Israel, concentrated in the Circassian towns of Kfar Kama and Rehaniya, is considered to have one of the highest levels of language maintenance in the diaspora.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Adyghe serves as the language of daily communication in the home, school, and public spaces.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] In 1958-1959, Israeli Circassians made contact for the first time with Circassians in the Caucasus and requested literary material in Adyghe, which they received.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] In 1976, the Adyghe language was introduced into the official school curriculum.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] It is a compulsory subject from 6th grade onward, and utilizes textbooks based on the literary standard of the Republic of Adygea.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Despite the dominance of the Shapsug dialect in speech, the written language taught in schools utilizes the Cyrillic alphabet and the Chemguy-based literary standard.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Kfar Kama is inhabited by the Shapsug tribe, while Rihaniya is inhabited by the Abzakh tribe.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Israeli variety of Adyghe also contains unique neologisms.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Even in diaspora communities with highly preserved spoken fluency, such as the compact Circassian settlements in Israel, literacy is a significant challenge; one survey showed that while 81.7% of respondents had advanced speaking proficiency, only 12% reported writing proficiency.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] In Jordan, the Adyghe language has historically enjoyed a relatively privileged status, though it currently faces significant pressure, as Arabic has become the dominant language for the younger generation, and the Adyghe language is often restricted to symbolic functions or domestic use.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Consequently, Adyghe in Jordan serves more as a folkloric marker of identity than a functional tool for daily communication.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Adyghe language in Jordan is currently classified as severely endangered due to a rapid disruption in intergenerational transmission.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] The decline of the language was triggered by migration, urbanization, and the dispersion of the Circassian population among the Arabic-speaking majority.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] For example, the expansion of Amman in the early 1900s transformed predominantly Circassian farming villages into diverse urban centres inhabited by Arabs, causing Circassians to become a minority in their original settlements.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Today, Arabic has almost entirely ousted Circassian as the primary language of communication within the home.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Surveys indicate that 21% of children use Circassian at home.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Because schools historically used Arabic as the sole medium of instruction, Circassian parents began speaking Arabic at home to ensure their children would not struggle academically.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Adyghe is taught in Prince Hamza Ibn Al-Hussein Secondary School, a school for Jordanian Circassians in Jordan's capital city of Amman.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] This school, established by Circassians with support from King Hussein of Jordan, is one of the first schools for the Adyghe communities outside Circassia.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] It has around 750 Jordanian Adyghe students, and aims to preserve the Adyghe language and traditions among future generations.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] The diaspora in Jordan has produced dictionaries and linguistic works, such as a Circassian-Arabic dictionary published in 1988.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Circassian Charity Association of Jordan also sponsors a school between Naur and Wadi Al-Seer that teaches the language.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Historically, various dialects were spoken by immigrants, including Shapsug, Bzhedug, (and Kabardian), but over time these dialects have merged.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Historically, the Golan Heights served as a centre for Circassian language preservation prior to the 1967 war.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] In the 1920s and 1930s, the "Circassian Society of Education and Union" in Quneitra published the newspaper *Mardj* in Circassian (using the Latin script), Arabic, and French, and established a school that taught the language alongside general subjects.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] In the late 20th century, the Circassian Charity Association in Damascus operated informal language circles to teach the Cyrillic script and preserve oral traditions.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] However, the language has declined due to the lack of state-supported education and the dominance of Arabic in all public spheres.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] After the Syrian defeat in the war, the Circassian population largely fled the Golan Heights region, which was occupied by the Israeli Army.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Many of Syria's ethnic Circassians have left the country and have repatriated to Adygea, Kabardino-Balkaria and Karachay-Cherkessia, as well as to partially recognised Republic of Abkhazia.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Circassian American community is multilingual, speaking languages including English, Circassian (Adyghe, Kabardian), and Arabic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] However, the community is currently experiencing a significant language shift away from their ethnic Adyghe language and toward English.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] English is the dominant language used in almost all public and social domains, utilized universally in the workplace and overwhelmingly with neighbors, non-Circassian friends, and even among Circassian peers.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Adyghe language remains preserved primarily within the home, specifically in intergenerational communication.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Circassian is predominantly spoken by the elder members of the community and is the primary language used when younger generations address their grandparents, representing over 52% of these interactions.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] A study found that a large majority of the New Jersey Circassian community (81.5%) agrees that learning the Circassian language is essential for maintaining their ethnic identity.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] However, some Circassian Americans have abandoned Adyghe fluency as redundant, focusing instead on Adyghe Khabze, traditional dances and folklore.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Circassian Benevolent Association (CBA) hosts a Sunday school where volunteers teach the Circassian language.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] In recent years, growing political pressure and the criminalization of civil society initiatives in Russia have forced many scholars and language activists to relocate, shifting the epicenter of Circassian language activism and cultural preservation to countries abroad, including the United States.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Following the Circassian Genocide and expulsion in 1864, the majority of Adyghe speakers were scattered across the Ottoman Empire.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] The language spoken in the diaspora has diverged from the literary forms in the Caucasus.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Diaspora communities often use Arabic or Turkish loanwords where the literary language uses Russian ones.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] The linguistic divergence between the Adyghe language spoken in the historical homeland and the language spoken by the diaspora, particularly in Turkey and the Middle East, is the result of over a century and a half of isolated development.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] This isolation, combined with the mixing of various dialects and the strong influence of local languages like Turkish and Arabic, led to significant phonetic, lexical, and semantic differences.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Some native Adyghe words acquired entirely new meanings in the diaspora.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] The word *гу*, which historically means "wagon" or "cart" in the literary language, has evolved to mean "automobile" or "car" among diaspora speakers.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Similarly, the word *ин* (big) is used in the diaspora to refer to an "elder," replacing the literary term *нэхъыжь*.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Due to intense influence of the Russian language, Russian loanwords in standart Adyghe are left exactly as is and not adapted to the language in terms of spelling or pronouncation.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Turkish linguistic influence led to the creation of calques (literal translations) for modern concepts.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] In some extreme cases, diaspora speakers even attach Turkish grammatical suffixes, such as the past tense *-miş* or the subjunctive *-dı*, directly to Adyghe roots, though native speakers often recognize these constructions as "non-Adyghe".
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] While the spoken and folkloric language of the diaspora evolved independently, this isolation has begun to diminish.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] With the advent of the internet and social media, the younger and middle generations in the diaspora are increasingly interacting with the Cyrillic-based literary language of the homeland.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] This exposure is initiating a slow but inevitable "literaturization" of the diaspora's language, gradually aligning their written and official communication with the literary standard.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] When conversing in Turkish, diaspora Circassians frequently embed native Adyghe terms to refer to specific traditional and unique cultural conventions, or use them as in-group slang.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Besides native vocabulary, the Adyghe language has accepted loanwsome ords from Turkic, Arabic, Persian, Russian and other languages.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] The appearance of Turkic loanwords in the Adyghe language can be dated to the 14th century due to interactions with the Golden Horde and Crimean Khanate.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] By the mid-19th century; Arabic words had begun to enter the language.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] Words such as *chapych* (kopeck) are pre-revolutionary loans from Russian.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/adyghe-language] In old borrowings, as a rule, the phonetic composition of borrowed words was adapted to the phonological system of the Adyghe language.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/aer-language] After the Partition of India in 1947, the Muslim speakers of the language migrated to Pakistan, while the Hindu speakers stayed in India.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/aer-language] Most of the Aer speakers in Pakistan live in Deh 333, near Hyderabad in lower Sindh.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/aer-language] The language was formed in the Indian subcontinent during the Delhi Sultanate and Mughal Empire due to the influence of Persian, Arabic, and Turkish on Indian languages.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/aer-language] A 1998 estimate concluded there were around 200 native speakers.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/aer-language] Current estimates, however, put the number of speakers at 150, further cementing its 'endangered' status.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/aer-language] Aer has been classified as one of the Gujarati languages.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/aer-language] Ethnologue reports that the closest language is Kachi Koli and especially its dialects Katai Meghwar and Kachi Bhil, and that most Aer speakers are bilingual in Sindhi.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/aer-language] Two varieties of Aer are Jikrio Goth Aer and Jamesabad Aer.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/aer-language] Aer is commonly not written, but when it is, it is written in a variety of the Arabic script.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Although Afrikaans has adopted words from other languages, including German, Malay, and Khoisan languages, an estimated 90 to 95% of its vocabulary is of Dutch origin.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Differences between Afrikaans and Dutch often lie in the more analytic morphology and grammar of Afrikaans, and different spellings.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] There is a large degree of mutual intelligibility between the two languages, especially in written form.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] The language's name comes directly from the Dutch word *Afrikaansch* (now spelled *Afrikaans*) meaning 'African'.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] It was previously called 'Cape Dutch' (*Kaap-Hollands* or *Kaap-Nederlands*), a term also used to refer to the early Cape settlers collectively, or the derogatory 'kitchen Dutch' (*kombuistaal*) from its use by slaves of colonial settlers "in the kitchen".
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] The Afrikaans language arose in the Dutch Cape Colony through a gradual divergence from European Dutch dialects during the 18th century.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] As early as the mid-18th century and as recently as the early-20th century, many in Southern Africa viewed pre-standardized Afrikaans as 'kitchen Dutch' (Afrikaans: *kombuistaal*), lacking the prestige accorded an officially recognised language like standard Dutch and English.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] In the 19th-century Boer republics, proto-Afrikaans was not yet widely seen by the Afrikaner population or its leaders as a separate language from standard Dutch.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Dutch was expressly the sole and only legally recognised language at that time.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Other early epithets in Southern Africa setting apart *Kaaps Hollands* ('Cape Dutch', i.e.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Proto-Afrikaans) as putatively beneath official Dutch language standards included *geradbraakt*, *gebroken* and *onbeschaafd Hollands* (respectively 'mutilated', 'broken', and 'uncivilised Dutch'), as well as *verkeerd Nederlands* ('incorrect Dutch').
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Thus, in his view, Afrikaans is neither a creole nor a direct descendant of Dutch, but rather a hybrid language born from two parallel transmission pathways (a semi-creole).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Most of the first settlers whose descendants today are the Afrikaners were from the United Provinces (now Netherlands), with up to one-sixth of the community of French Huguenot origin, and a seventh from Germany.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] African and Asian workers, Cape Coloured children of European settlers and Khoikhoi women, and slaves contributed to the development of Afrikaans.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] The slave population comprised people from East Africa, West Africa, Mughal India, Madagascar, and the Dutch East Indies (modern Indonesia).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Many were also indigenous Khoisan people, who were valued as interpreters, domestic servants, and labourers.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Many free and enslaved women married or cohabited with male Dutch settlers.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Valkhoff argued that 75% of children born to female slaves in the Dutch Cape Colony between 1652 and 1672 had a Dutch father.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Beginning in about 1815, Afrikaans started to replace Malay as the language of instruction in Muslim schools in South Africa, written in Arabic Afrikaans.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] These are the earliest known works written in Afrikaans, at a time when Standard Dutch was the main written language.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Later, Afrikaans, now written with the Latin script, started to appear in newspapers and political and religious works in around 1850 (alongside the already established Dutch).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] In 1875 a group of Afrikaans-speakers from the Cape formed the *Genootskap vir Regte Afrikaaners* ('Society for Real Afrikaners'), and published a number of books in Afrikaans, including grammars, dictionaries, religious materials, and histories.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Until the early 20th century Afrikaans was considered a Dutch dialect, alongside Standard Dutch, which it eventually replaced as an official language.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Before the Boer wars, "and indeed for some time afterwards, Afrikaans was regarded as inappropriate for educated discourse.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] In 1925 Afrikaans was recognised by the South African government as a distinct language rather than simply a vernacular of Dutch.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] On 8 May 1925, 23 years after the Second Boer War ended, the Official Languages of the Union Act, 1925 was passed—mostly due to the efforts of the Afrikaans language movement—at a joint sitting of the House of Assembly and the Senate, in which the Afrikaans language was declared a variety of Dutch.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] The Constitution of 1961 reversed the position of Afrikaans and Dutch, so that English and Afrikaans were the official languages and Afrikaans was deemed to include Dutch.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] The Constitution of 1983 removed any mention of Dutch altogether.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] The Afrikaans Language Monument is on a hill overlooking Paarl in the Western Cape Province.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Officially opened on 10 October 1975, it was erected on the 100th anniversary of the founding of the Society of Real Afrikaners, and the 50th anniversary of Afrikaans being declared an official language of South Africa in distinction to Dutch.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] The earliest Afrikaans texts were some doggerel verses from 1795 and a dialogue transcribed by a Dutch traveller in 1825.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Afrikaans used the Latin alphabet around this time, although the Cape Muslim community used the Arabic script.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Meurant published his *Zamenspraak tusschen Klaas Waarzegger en Jan Twyfelaar* (*Conversation between Nicholas Truthsayer and John Doubter*), which is considered the first book published in Afrikaans.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] The first grammar book was published in 1876; a bilingual dictionary was published in 1902.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] The main modern Afrikaans dictionary in use is the *Verklarende Handwoordeboek van die Afrikaanse Taal* (HAT).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] A new authoritative dictionary, *Woordeboek van die Afrikaanse Taal* (WAT), was under development As of 2018.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] The official orthography of Afrikaans is the *Afrikaanse Woordelys en Spelreëls*, compiled by *Die Taalkommissie*.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] The Afrikaners primarily were Protestants, of the Dutch Reformed Church of the 17th century.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Their religious practices were later influenced in South Africa by British ministries during the 1800s.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] A landmark in the language's development was the translation of the Bible into Afrikaans.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] While significant advances had been made in the textual criticism of the Bible, especially the Greek New Testament, the 1933 translation followed the Textus Receptus and was closely akin to the *Statenbijbel*.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Before this, most Cape Dutch-Afrikaans speakers had to rely on the Dutch *Statenbijbel*.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] This *Statenvertaling* had its origins with the Synod of Dordrecht of 1618 and was thus in an archaic form of Dutch.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] This was hard for Dutch speakers to understand, and increasingly unintelligible for Afrikaans speakers.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Hoogehout, Arnoldus Pannevis, and Stephanus Jacobus du Toit were the first Afrikaans Bible translators.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] An important landmark in the translation of the Scriptures as C.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Hoogehout's 1878 translation of the *Evangelie volgens Markus* (Gospel of Mark, lit.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] 'Gospel according to Mark'), but it was never published.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] The manuscript is in the South African National Library, Cape Town.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] The first official translation of the entire Bible into Afrikaans was in 1933 by J.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] In 1983 a fresh translation marked the 50th anniversary of the 1933 version.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] It was influenced by Eugene Nida's theory of dynamic equivalence, which focused on finding the nearest equivalent in the receptor language to the idea that the Greek, Hebrew, or Aramaic conveyed.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] A new translation, *Die Bybel: 'n Direkte Vertaling* was released in November 2020.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] It is the first truly ecumenical translation of the Bible in Afrikaans as translators from various churches, including the Roman Catholic and Anglican Churches, were involved.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Afrikaans descended from Dutch dialects in the 17th century.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] It belongs to a West Germanic sub-group, the Low Franconian languages.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Other West Germanic languages related to Afrikaans are German, English, the Frisian languages, Yiddish, and the unstandardised language Low German.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Besides South-Africa, Afrikaans is also widely spoken in Namibia.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Before independence, Afrikaans had equal status with German as an official language.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Since independence in 1990, Afrikaans has had constitutional recognition as a national, but not official, language.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] There is a much smaller number of Afrikaans speakers among Zimbabwe's white minority, as most have left the country since 1980.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Afrikaans was also a medium of instruction for schools in Bophuthatswana, an Apartheid-era Bantustan.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Eldoret, Kenya, was founded by Afrikaners.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] There are also around 30,000 South Africans in the Netherlands, of which the majority are of Afrikaans-speaking Afrikaner and Coloured South-African descent.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] A much smaller and unknown number of Afrikaans speakers also reside in the Dutch Caribbean.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Contrary to popular belief, the majority of Afrikaans speakers today are not Afrikaners or Boers, but Coloureds.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] In 1976, secondary-school pupils in Soweto began a rebellion in response to the government's decision that Afrikaans be used as the language of instruction for half the subjects taught in non-White schools (with English continuing for the other half).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Although English is the mother tongue of only 8.2% of the population, it is the language most widely understood, and the second language of a majority of South Africans.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Afrikaans is more widely spoken than English in the Northern and Western Cape provinces, several hundred kilometres from Soweto.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] The Black community's opposition to Afrikaans and preference for continuing English instruction was underlined when the government rescinded the policy one month after the uprising: 96% of Black schools chose English (over Afrikaans or native languages) as the language of instruction.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Afrikaans-medium schools were also accused of using language policy to deter Black African parents.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Some of these parents, in part supported by provincial departments of education, initiated litigation which enabled enrolment with English as language of instruction.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] By 2006 there were 300 single-medium Afrikaans schools, compared to 2,500 in 1994, after most converted to dual-medium education.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Due to Afrikaans being viewed as the "language of the white oppressor" by some, pressure has been increased to remove Afrikaans as a teaching language in South African universities, resulting in bloody student protests in 2015.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Under South Africa's Constitution of 1996, Afrikaans remains an official language, and has equal status to English and ten other languages.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] The new policy means that the use of Afrikaans is now often reduced in favour of English, or to accommodate the other official languages.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] In 1996, for example, the South African Broadcasting Corporation reduced the amount of television airtime in Afrikaans, while South African Airways dropped its Afrikaans name *Suid-Afrikaanse Lugdiens* from its livery.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Similarly, South Africa's diplomatic missions overseas now display the name of the country only in English and their host country's language, and not in Afrikaans.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Meanwhile, the constitution of the Western Cape, which went into effect in 1998, declares Afrikaans to be an official language of the province alongside English and Xhosa.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] The Afrikaans-language general-interest family magazine *Huisgenoot* has the largest readership of any magazine in the country.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] The author of the article, Bronwyn Davies, was an English-speaking South African.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] An estimated 90 to 95 percent of the Afrikaans lexicon is ultimately of Dutch origin, and there are few lexical differences between the two languages.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Afrikaans has a considerably more regular morphology, grammar, and spelling.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] There is a high degree of mutual intelligibility between the two languages, particularly in written form.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Afrikaans acquired some lexical and syntactical borrowings from other languages such as Malay, Khoisan languages, Portuguese, German and Bantu languages.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Afrikaans has also been significantly influenced by South African English, especially in the Western Cape.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Dutch speakers are confronted with fewer non-cognates when listening to Afrikaans than the other way round.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Mutual intelligibility thus tends to be asymmetrical, as it is easier for Dutch speakers to understand Afrikaans than for Afrikaans speakers to understand Dutch.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] In general, mutual intelligibility between Dutch and Afrikaans is far better than between Dutch and Frisian or between Danish and Swedish.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] The South African poet writer Breyten Breytenbach, attempting to visualise the language distance for Anglophones, once remarked that the differences between (Standard) Dutch and Afrikaans are comparable to those between the Received Pronunciation and Southern American English.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Afrikaans is an official language of the Republic of South Africa and a recognised national language of the Republic of Namibia.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Post-apartheid South Africa has seen a loss of preferential treatment by the government for Afrikaans, in terms of education, social events, media (TV and radio), and general status throughout the country, given that it now shares its place as official language with ten other languages.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Nevertheless, Afrikaans remains more prevalent in the media – radio, newspapers and television – than any of the other official languages except English.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] More than 300 book titles in Afrikaans are published annually.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] South African census figures suggest a decreasing number of first language Afrikaans speakers in South Africa from 13.5% in 2011 to 10.6% in 2022.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] The South African Institute of Race Relations (SAIRR) projects that a growing majority of Afrikaans speakers will be Coloured.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Afrikaans speakers experience higher employment rates than other South African language groups, though as of 2012 half a million were unemployed.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Despite the challenges of demotion and emigration that it faces in South Africa, the Afrikaans vernacular remains competitive, being popular in DSTV pay channels and several internet sites, while generating high newspaper and music CD sales.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] A resurgence in Afrikaans popular music since the late 1990s has invigorated the language, especially among a younger generation of South Africans.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] A recent trend is the increased availability of pre-school educational CDs and DVDs.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Such media also prove popular with the extensive Afrikaans-speaking emigrant communities who seek to retain language proficiency in a household context.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Afrikaans-language cinema showed signs of new vigour in the early 21st century.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] The 2007 film *Ouma se slim kind*, the first full-length Afrikaans movie since *Paljas* in 1998, is seen as the dawn of a new era in Afrikaans cinema.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Several short films have been created and more feature-length movies, such as *Poena Is Koning* and *Bakgat* (both in 2008) have been produced, besides the 2011 Afrikaans-language film *Skoonheid*, which was the first Afrikaans film to screen at the Cannes Film Festival.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] The film *Platteland* was also released in 2011.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] The Afrikaans film industry started gaining international recognition via the likes of big Afrikaans Hollywood film stars, like Charlize Theron (*Monster*) and Sharlto Copley (*District 9*) promoting their mother tongue.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] SABC 3 announced early in 2009 that it would increase Afrikaans programming due to the "growing Afrikaans-language market and [their] need for working capital as Afrikaans advertising is the only advertising that sells in the current South African television market".
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] In April 2009, SABC3 started screening several Afrikaans-language programmes.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] There is a groundswell movement within Afrikaans to be inclusive, and to promote itself along with the indigenous official languages.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] In Namibia, the percentage of Afrikaans speakers declined from 11.4% (2001 Census) to 10.4% (2011 Census).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Some native speakers of Bantu languages and English also speak Afrikaans as a second language.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] It is widely taught in South African schools, with about 10.3 million second-language students.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Afrikaans is offered at many universities outside South Africa, including in the Netherlands, Belgium, Germany, Poland, Russia and the United States.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] In Afrikaans grammar, there is no distinction between the infinitive and present forms of verbs, with the exception of the verbs 'to be' and 'to have'.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] In addition, verbs do not conjugate differently depending on the subject.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Only a handful of Afrikaans verbs have a preterite, namely the auxiliary *wees* ('to be'), the modal verbs, and the verb *dink* ('to think').
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] The preterite of *mag* ('may') is rare in contemporary Afrikaans.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] All other verbs use the perfect tense, het + past participle (ge-), for the past.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Therefore, there is no distinction in Afrikaans between *I drank* and *I have drunk*.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] When telling a longer story, Afrikaans speakers usually avoid the perfect and simply use the present tense, or historical present tense instead (as is possible, but less common, in English as well).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] A particular feature of Afrikaans is its use of the double negative; it is classified in Afrikaans as **ontkennende vorm** and is something that is absent from the other West Germanic standard languages.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Both French and San origins have been suggested for double negation in Afrikaans.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] While double negation is still found in Low Franconian dialects in West Flanders and in some "isolated" villages in the centre of the Netherlands (such as Garderen), it takes a different form, which is not found in Afrikaans.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] The *-ne* was the Middle Dutch way to negate but it has been suggested that since *-ne* became highly non-voiced, *nie* or *niet* was needed to complement the *-ne*.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] With time the *-ne* disappeared in most Dutch dialects.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] A notable exception to this is the use of the negating grammar form that coincides with negating the English present participle.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] In this case there is only a single negation.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Hy is in die hospitaal, maar hy eet nie.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Hij is in het ziekenhuis, maar hij eet niet.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] English: He is in [the] hospital, though he doesn't eat.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Certain words in Afrikaans would be contracted.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] For example, *moet nie*, which literally means 'must not', usually becomes *moenie*; although one does not have to write or say it like this, virtually all Afrikaans speakers will change the two words to *moenie* in the same way as *do not* is contracted to *don't* in English.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] The Dutch word *het* ('it' in English) does not correspond to *het* in Afrikaans.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] The Dutch words corresponding to Afrikaans *het* are *heb*, *hebt*, *heeft* and *hebben*.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Following early dialectal studies of Afrikaans, it was theorised that three main historical dialects probably existed after the Great Trek in the 1830s.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] These dialects are the Northern Cape, Western Cape, and Eastern Cape dialects.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Northern Cape dialect may have resulted from contact between Dutch settlers and the Khoekhoe people between the Great Karoo and the Kunene, and Eastern Cape dialect between the Dutch and the Xhosa.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Remnants of these dialects still remain in present-day Afrikaans, although the standardising effect of Standard Afrikaans has contributed to a great levelling of differences in modern times.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Oranjerivier-Afrikaans (Orange River Afrikaans) is a major variety, including the Oranjerivier Afrikaans spoken by whites and Griqua Afrikaans spoken by Griqua as well as Namakwalands.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] There is also a prison cant, known as Sabela, which is based on Afrikaans, yet heavily influenced by Zulu.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] This language is used as a secret language in prison and is taught to initiates.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Patagonian Afrikaans is a distinct dialect of Afrikaans that is spoken by the 650-member South African community of Argentina, in the region of Patagonia.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Namibian Afrikaans is a variety of Afrikaans spoken in Namibia.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] The country was governed by South Africa until 1990, which had favoured Afrikaans.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Before that, Dutch had been introduced when the Dutch occupied Walvis Bay and the surrounding area.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Due to the early settlement of a Cape Malay community in Cape Town, who are now known as Coloureds, numerous Classical Malay words were brought into Afrikaans.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Some of these words entered Dutch via people arriving from what is now known as Indonesia as part of their colonial heritage.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Some words originally came from Portuguese such as *sambreel* ('umbrella') from the Portuguese *sombreiro*, *kraal* ('pen/cattle enclosure') from the Portuguese *curral* and *mielie* ('corn', from *milho*).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Some of these words also exist in Dutch, like *sambreel* 'parasol', though usage is less common and meanings can slightly differ.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Some of these words also exist in Dutch, though with a more specific meaning: *assegaai* for example means 'South-African tribal javelin' and *karos* means 'South-African tribal blanket of animal hides'.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Loanwords from Bantu languages in Afrikaans include the names of indigenous birds, such as *mahem* and *sakaboela*, and indigenous plants, such as *maroela* and *tamboekie(gras)*.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] The revoking of the Edict of Nantes on 22 October 1685 was a milestone in the history of South Africa, for it marked the beginning of the great Huguenot exodus from France.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] It is estimated that between 250,000 and 300,000 Protestants left France between 1685 and 1700; out of these, according to Louvois, 100,000 had received military training.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] A measure of the calibre of these immigrants and of their acceptance by host countries (in particular South Africa) is given by H.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Morton in his book: *In Search of South Africa* (London, 1948).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] The Huguenots were responsible for a great linguistic contribution to Afrikaans, particularly in terms of military terminology as many of them fought on the battlefields during the wars of the Great Trek.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Most of the words in this list are descendants from Dutch borrowings from French, Old French or Latin, and are not direct influences from French on Afrikaans.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] The Afrikaans writing system is based on Dutch, using the 26 letters of the ISO basic Latin alphabet, plus 16 additional vowel sounds represented by adding diacritics.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] The hyphen (e.g. in a compound like *see-eend* 'sea duck'), apostrophe (e.g.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] *ma's* 'mothers'), and a whitespace character (e.g. in multi-word units like *Dooie See* 'Dead Sea') is part of the orthography of words, while the indefinite article *ŉ* is a ligature.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] All the alphabet letters, including those with diacritics, have capital letters as allographs; the *ŉ* does not have a capital letter allograph.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] This means that Afrikaans has 88 graphemes with allographs in total.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] In Afrikaans, many consonants are dropped from the earlier Dutch spelling.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] For example, **slechts** ('only') in Dutch becomes **slegs** in Afrikaans.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Also, Afrikaans and some Dutch dialects make no distinction between /s/ and /z/, having merged the latter into the former; while the word for "south" is written **zuid** in Dutch, it is spelled **suid** in Afrikaans (as well as dialectal Dutch writings) to represent this merger.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Similarly, the Dutch digraph **ĳ**, normally pronounced as /ɛi/, corresponds to Afrikaans **y**, except where it replaces the Dutch suffix **–lijk** which is pronounced as /lək/, as in **waarschijnlijk* > *waarskynlik**.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Another difference is the indefinite article, **'n** in Afrikaans and *een* in Dutch.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] "A book" is **'n boek** in Afrikaans, whereas it is either **een boek** or **'n boek** in Dutch.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] This **'n** is usually pronounced as just a weak vowel, [ə], just like English "a".
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] The diminutive suffix in Afrikaans is **-tjie**, **-djie** or **-ie**, whereas in Dutch it is **-tje** or **dje**, hence a "bit" is ŉ *bie**tjie*** in Afrikaans and *bee**tje*** in Dutch.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] The letters *c*, *q*, *x*, and *z* occur almost exclusively in borrowings from French, English, Greek and Latin.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] This is usually because words that had *c* and *ch* in the original Dutch are spelled with *k* and *g*, respectively, in Afrikaans.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Similarly original *qu* and *x* are most often spelt *kw* and *ks*, respectively.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] For example, **ekwatoriaal** instead of *equatoriaal*, and **ekskuus** instead of *excuus*.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Diacritics are ignored when alphabetising, but it is important to include them even if they are difficult to type.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] For example, **geëet** ("ate") instead of the 3 e's alongside each other: ***geeet**, which can never occur in Afrikaans, or **sê**, which translates to "say", whereas **se** is a possessive form.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] The primary function of the acute accent (*á*, *é*, *í*, *ó*, *ú, ý)* is to indicate an emphasised syllable.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] The acute is only placed on an *i* if that is the only vowel in an emphasised word: *wil* ('want' (verb)) becomes *wíl*, but *lui* ('lazy') becomes *lúi.* Only a few non-loan words are spelled with acutes, e.g.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] A few short words in Afrikaans take initial apostrophes.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] In modern Afrikaans, these words are always written in lower case (except when writing in all-capitals); if they occur at the beginning of a sentence, the following word that has no initial apostrophe is capitalised instead.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Three examples of such apostrophed words are **'k, 't, 'n**.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] The last (the indefinite article) is the only such word common in modern written Afrikaans, since the others are shortened versions of words that are usually written out (**ek** and **het**, respectively) and are rarely found outside of a poetic context.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] The apostrophe and the following letter are regarded as two separate characters, and are never written using a single glyph, although a single-character variant of the indefinite article appears in Unicode, *ŉ*.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] For more on the pronunciation of the letters below, see *Help:IPA/Afrikaans*.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Alle menslike wesens word vry, met gelyke waardigheid en regte, gebore.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Hulle het rede en gewete en behoort in die gees van broederskap teenoor mekaar op te tree.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Die Here is my Herder, niks sal my ontbreek nie.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Hy laat my neerlê in groen weivelde; na waters waar rus is, lei Hy my heen.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Hy verkwik my siel; Hy lei my in die spore van geregtigheid, om sy Naam ontwil.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Al gaan ek ook in 'n dal van doodskaduwee, ek sal geen onheil vrees nie; want U is met my: u stok en u staf die vertroos my.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Die Here is my Herder, ek kom niks kort nie.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Hy bring my by waters waar daar vrede is.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Hy lei my op die regte paaie tot eer van Sy naam.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Selfs al gaan ek deur donker dieptes, sal ek nie bang wees nie, want U is by my.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Ons Vader in die hemel, laat u Naam geheilig word.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Laat u wil hier op aarde uitgevoer word soos in die hemel.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Gee ons die porsie brood wat ons vir vandag nodig het.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] En vergeef ons ons sondeskuld soos ons ook óns skuldenaars vergewe het.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Bewaar ons sodat ons nie aan verleiding sal toegee nie; maar bevry ons van die greep van die bose.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Want aan U behoort die koningskap, en die krag, en die heerlikheid, vir altyd.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Onse Vader wat in die hemel is, laat U Naam geheilig word; laat U koninkryk kom; laat U wil geskied op die aarde, net soos in die hemel.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afrikaans-alphabet] Gee ons vandag ons daaglikse brood; en vergeef ons ons skulde soos ons ons skuldenaars vergewe en laat ons nie in die versoeking nie maar verlos ons van die bose Want aan U behoort die koninkryk en die krag en die heerlikheid tot in ewigheid.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] The **Afroasiatic languages** (also known as the **Afro-Asiatic**, **Afrasian**, **Hamito-Semitic**, or **Semito-Hamitic languages**) are a language family (or *phylum*) of about 400 languages spoken predominantly in West Asia, North Africa, the Horn of Africa, and parts of the Sahara and Sahel.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Over 500 million people are native speakers of an Afroasiatic language, constituting the fourth-largest language family after Indo-European, Sino-Tibetan, and Niger–Congo.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Most linguists divide the family into six branches: Berber, Chadic, Cushitic, Egyptian, Omotic, and Semitic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] The vast majority of Afroasiatic languages are considered indigenous to the African continent, including all those not belonging to the Semitic branch (which originated in West Asia).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Other Afroasiatic languages with millions of native speakers include the Semitic Tigrinya, Tigre and Modern Hebrew, the Cushitic Beja, Sidama and Afar languages, the Berber languages (Shilha, Kabyle, Central Atlas Tamazight, Shawiya and Tarifit), and the Omotic Wolaitta language.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Most languages of the non-Semitic branches (especially Chadic and Omotic) have far fewer speakers, and many Afroasiatic languages in Africa are vulnerable or endangered.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] There are many well-attested Afroasiatic languages from antiquity that have since died or gone extinct, including Egyptian and the Semitic languages Akkadian, Biblical Hebrew, Phoenician, Amorite, and Ugaritic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] There is no consensus among historical linguists as to precisely where or when the common ancestor of all Afroasiatic languages, known as Proto-Afroasiatic, was originally spoken.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] However, most agree that the Afroasiatic homeland was located somewhere in Eastern North Africa or Northern East Africa, with specific proposals including the Horn of Africa, Egypt, and the eastern Sahara.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] A significant minority of scholars argues for an origin in the Levant.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Even the latest plausible dating for its proto-language makes Afroasiatic the oldest language family accepted by contemporary linguists.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Reconstructed timelines of when Proto-Afroasiatic was spoken vary extensively, with dates ranging from 18,000 BC to 8,000 BC.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] While systematic sound laws have not yet been established to explain the relationships between the various branches of Afroasiatic, the languages share a number of common features.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] One of the most important for establishing membership in the branch is a common set of pronouns.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Other widely shared features include a prefix m- which creates nouns from verbs, evidence for alternations between the vowel "a" and a high vowel in the forms of the verb, similar methods of marking gender and plurality, and some details of phonology such as the presence of pharyngeal fricatives.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] In current scholarship, the most common names for the family are *Afroasiatic* (or *Afro-Asiatic*), *Hamito-Semitic*, and *Semito-Hamitic*.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Other proposed names that have yet to find widespread acceptance include *Erythraic*/*Erythraean*, *Lisramic*, *Noahitic*, and *Lamekhite*.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Friedrich Müller introduced the name *Hamito-Semitic* to describe the family in his *Grundriss der Sprachwissenschaft* (1876).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] The variant *Semito-Hamitic* is mostly used in older Russian sources.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] The elements of the name were derived from the names of two sons of Noah as attested in the Book of Genesis's Table of Nations passage: "Semitic" from the first-born Shem, and "Hamitic" from the second-born Ham (Genesis 5:32).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Within the Table of Nations, each of Noah's sons is presented as the common progenitor of various people groups deemed to be closely related: among others Shem was the father of the Jews, Assyrians, and Arameans, while Ham was the father of the Egyptians and Cushites.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] The term *Semitic* for the Semitic languages had already been coined in 1781 by August Ludwig von Schlözer, following an earlier suggestion by Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz in 1710.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] *Hamitic* was first used by Ernest Renan in 1855 to refer to languages that appeared similar to the Semitic languages, but were not themselves provably a part of the family.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] The belief in a connection between Africans and the Biblical Ham, which had existed at least as far back as Isidore of Seville in the 6th century AD, led scholars in the early 19th century to speak vaguely of "Hamian" or "Hamitish" languages.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] The term *Hamito-Semitic* has largely fallen out of favor among linguists writing in English, but is still frequently used in the scholarship of various other languages, such as German.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Several issues with the label *Hamito-Semitic* have led many scholars to abandon the term and criticize its continued use.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] One common objection is that the *Hamitic* component inaccurately suggests that a monophyletic "Hamitic" branch exists alongside Semitic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] In addition, Joseph Greenberg has argued that *Hamitic* possesses racial connotations, and that "Hamito-Semitic" overstates the centrality of the Semitic languages within the family.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] By contrast, Victor Porkhomovsky suggests that the label is simply an inherited convention, and does not imply a duality of Semitic and "Hamitic" any more than *Indo-European* implies a duality of Indic and "European".
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Because of its use by several important scholars and in the titles of significant works of scholarship, the total replacement of *Hamito-Semitic* is difficult.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] While Greenberg ultimately popularized the name "Afroasiatic" in 1960, it appears to have been coined originally by Maurice Delafosse, as French *afroasiatique*, in 1914.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] The name refers to the fact that it is the only major language family with large populations in both Africa and Asia.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Due to concerns that "Afroasiatic" could imply the inclusion of *all* languages spoken across Africa and Asia, the name "Afrasian" (Russian: *afrazijskije*) was proposed by Igor Diakonoff in 1980.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] At present it predominantly sees use among Russian scholars.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] The names *Lisramic*—based on the Afroasiastic root **lis-* ("tongue") and the Egyptian word *rmṯ* ("person")—and *Erythraean*—referring to the core area around which the languages are spoken, the Red Sea—have also been proposed.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Scholars generally consider Afroasiatic to have between five and eight branches.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] The five that are universally agreed upon are Berber (also called "Libyco-Berber"), Chadic, Cushitic, Egyptian, and Semitic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Most specialists consider the Omotic languages to constitute a sixth branch.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Due to the presumed distance of relationship between the various branches, many scholars prefer to refer to Afroasiatic as a "linguistic phylum" rather than a "language family".
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Victoria Almansa-Villatoro and Silvia Štubňová Nigrelli write that there are about 400 languages in Afroasiatic; Ethnologue lists 375 languages.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Many scholars estimate fewer languages; exact numbers vary depending on the definitions of "language" and "dialect".
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] The Berber (or Libyco-Berber) languages are spoken today by perhaps 16 million people.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] They are often considered to constitute a single language with multiple dialects.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Other scholars, however, argue that they are a group of around twelve languages, about as different from each other as the Romance or Germanic languages.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] In the past, Berber languages were spoken throughout North Africa except in Egypt; since the 7th century CE, however, they have been heavily affected by Arabic and have been replaced by it in many places.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Two extinct languages are potentially related to modern Berber.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] The first is the Numidian language, represented by over a thousand short inscriptions in the Libyco-Berber alphabet, found throughout North Africa and dating from the 2nd century BCE onward.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] The second is the Guanche language, which was formerly spoken on the Canary Islands and went extinct in the 17th century CE.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] The first longer written examples of modern Berber varieties date only from the 16th or 17th centuries CE.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Chadic languages number between 150 and 190, making Chadic the largest family in Afroasiatic by number of extant languages.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] The Chadic languages are typically divided into three major branches, East Chadic, Central Chadic, and West Chadic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Most Chadic languages are located in the Chad Basin, with the exception of Hausa.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Hausa is the largest Chadic language by native speakers, and is spoken by a large number of people as a lingua franca in Northern Nigeria.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] It may have as many as 80 to 100 million first- and second-language speakers.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Eight other Chadic languages have around 100,000 speakers; other Chadic languages often have few speakers and may be in danger of extinction.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Only about 40 Chadic languages have been fully described by linguists.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] There are about 30 Cushitic languages, more if Omotic is included, spoken around the Horn of Africa, and in Sudan and Tanzania.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] The Cushitic family is traditionally split into four branches: the single language of Beja (c.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] 3 million speakers), the Agaw languages, Eastern Cushitic, and Southern Cushitic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Only one Cushitic language, Oromo, has more than 25 million speakers; other languages with more than a million speakers include Somali, Afar, Hadiyya, and Sidaama.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Many Cushitic languages have relatively few speakers.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Cushitic does not appear to be related to the written ancient languages known from its area, Meroitic or Old Nubian.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] The oldest text in a Cushitic language probably dates from around 1770; written orthographies were developed for a select number of Cushitic languages only in the early 20th century.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] The Egyptian branch consists of the stages and dialects of a single language, Egyptian (often called "Ancient Egyptian"), which was historically spoken in the lower Nile Valley.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Egyptian is first attested in writing around 3000 BCE and finally went extinct around 1300 CE, making it the language with the longest written history in the world.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Egyptian is usually divided into two major periods, Earlier Egyptian (c.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] 3000 – 1300 BCE), which is further subdivided into Old Egyptian and Middle Egyptian, and Later Egyptian (1300 BCE – 1300 CE), which is further subdivided into Late Egyptian, Demotic, and Coptic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Coptic is the only stage written alphabetically to show vowels, whereas Egyptian was previously written in Egyptian hieroglyphs, which represent only consonants.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] In the Coptic period, there is evidence for six major dialects, which presumably existed previously, but are obscured by pre-Coptic writing; additionally, Middle Egyptian appears to be based on a different dialect than Old Egyptian, which in turn shows dialectal similarities to Late Egyptian.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Egyptian was replaced by Arabic as the spoken language of Egypt, but Coptic continues to be the liturgical language of the Coptic Orthodox Church.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] 30 Omotic languages are still mostly undescribed by linguists.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] They are all spoken in southwest Ethiopia except for the Ganza language, spoken in Sudan.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Omotic is typically split into North Omotic (or Damotic) and South Omotic (or Aroid), with the latter more influenced by the Nilotic languages; it is unclear whether the Dizoid group of Omotic languages belongs to the Northern or Southern group.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] The two Omotic languages with the most speakers are Wolaitta and Gamo-Gofa-Dawro, with about 1.2 million speakers each.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] A majority of specialists consider Omotic to constitute a sixth branch of Afroasiatic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Omotic was formerly considered part of the Cushitic branch; some scholars continue to consider it part of Cushitic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Other scholars have questioned whether it is Afroasiatic at all, due its lack of several typical aspects of Afroasiatic morphology.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] There are between 40 and 80 languages in the Semitic family.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Today, Semitic languages are spoken across North Africa, West Asia, and the Horn of Africa, as well as on the island of Malta, making them the sole Afroasiatic branch with members originating outside Africa.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Arabic, spoken in both Asia and Africa, is by far the most widely spoken Afroasiatic language today, with around 300-411 million native speakers, while the Ethiopian Amharic language has around 25-35 million; collectively, Semitic is the largest branch of Afroasiatic by number of current speakers.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Most authorities divide Semitic into two branches: East Semitic, which includes the extinct Akkadian language, and West Semitic, which includes Arabic, Aramaic, the Canaanite languages (including Hebrew), as well as the Ethiopian Semitic languages such as Geʽez and Amharic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] The classification within West Semitic remains contested.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] The only group with an African origin is Ethiopian Semitic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] The oldest written attestations of Semitic languages come from Mesopotamia, Northern Syria, and Egypt and date as early as c.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] There is no agreement on the relationships between and subgrouping of the different Afroasiatic branches.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Whereas Marcel Cohen (1947) claimed he saw no evidence for internal subgroupings, numerous other scholars have made proposals, with Carsten Peust counting 27 as of 2012.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Common trends in proposals as of 2019 include using common or lacking grammatical features to argue that Omotic was the first language to branch off, often followed by Chadic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] In contrast to scholars who argue for an early split of Chadic from Afroasiatic, scholars of the Russian school tend to argue that Chadic and Egyptian are closely related, and scholars who rely on percentage of shared lexicon often group Chadic with Berber.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Three scholars who agree on an early split between Omotic and the other subbranches, but little else, are Harold Fleming (1983), Christopher Ehret (1995), and Lionel Bender (1997).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] In contrast, scholars relying on shared lexicon often produce a Cushitic-Omotic group.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Additionally, the minority of scholars who favor an Asian origin of Afroasiatic tend to place Semitic as the first branch to split off.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Disagreement on which features are innovative and which are inherited from Proto-Afroasiatic produces radically different trees, as can be seen by comparing the trees produced by Ehret and Igor Diakonoff.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Peust notes that other factors that can obscure genetic relationships between languages include the poor state of present documentation and understanding of particular language families (historically with Egyptian, presently with Omotic).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Gene Gragg likewise argues that more needs to be known about Omotic still, and that Afroasiatic linguists have still not found convincing isoglosses on which to base genetic distinctions.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] One way of avoiding the problem of determining which features are original and which are inherited is to use a computational methodology such as lexicostatistics, with one of the earliest attempts by Fleming in 1983.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] This is also the method used by Alexander Militarev and Sergei Starostin to create a family tree.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Fleming (2006) was a more recent attempt by Fleming, with a different result from Militarev and Starostin.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Hezekiah Bacovcin and David Wilson argue that this methodology is invalid for discerning linguistic sub-relationship.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] They note the method's inability to detect various strong commonalities even between well-studied branches of AA.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] It has been suggested that if the original Afroasiatic-speaking people did indeed originate from southern Egypt, Central Sudan and/or Ethiopia, that they might have migrated up the Nile and intermingled with the Natufian population inhabiting the Levant and parts of the Sinai peninsula.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] This created a spread vector in and outside of Africa proper into the Levant, Middle East and Arabian peninsula which gave rise to a higher-order branch ancestral to both Cushitic and Semitic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] The variety spoken by those who stayed in the Northeast of the continent would become Egyptian over time.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] A relationship between Hebrew, Arabic, and Aramaic and the Berber languages was perceived as early as the 9th century CE by the Hebrew grammarian and physician Judah ibn Quraysh, who is regarded as a forerunner of Afroasiatic studies.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] The French orientalist Guillaume Postel had also pointed out similarities between Hebrew, Arabic, and Aramaic in 1538, and Hiob Ludolf noted similarities also to Geʽez and Amharic in 1701.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] This family was formally described and named "Semitic" by August Ludwig von Schlözer in 1781.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] In 1844, Theodor Benfey first described the relationship between Semitic and the Egyptian language and connected both to the Berber and the Cushitic languages (which he called "Ethiopic").
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Newman suggested a relationship between Semitic and the Hausa language, an idea that was taken up by early scholars of Afroasiatic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] In 1855, Ernst Renan named these languages, related to Semitic but not Semitic, "Hamitic", in 1860 Carl Lottner proposed that they belonged to a single language family, and in 1876 Friedrich Müller first described them as a "Hamito-Semitic" language family.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Müller assumed that there existed a distinct "Hamitic" branch of the family that consisted of Egyptian, Berber, and Cushitic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] He did not include the Chadic languages, though contemporary Egyptologist Karl Richard Lepsius argued for the relation of Hausa to the Berber languages.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] An important development in the history of Afroasiatic scholarship – and the history of African linguistics – was the creation of the "Hamitic theory" or "Hamitic hypothesis" by Lepsius, fellow Egyptologist Christian Bunsen, and linguist Christian Bleek.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] This theory connected the "Hamites", the originators of Hamitic languages, with (supposedly culturally superior) "Caucasians", who were assumed to have migrated into Africa and intermixed with indigenous "Negroid" Africans in ancient times.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] The "Hamitic theory" would serve as the basis for Carl Meinhof's highly influential classification of African languages in his 1912 book **Die Sprache der Hamiten**.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] On one hand, the "Hamitic" classification was justified partially based on linguistic features: for example, Meinhof split the presently-understood Chadic family into "Hamito-Chadic", and an unrelated non-Hamitic "Chadic" based on which languages possessed grammatical gender.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] On the other hand, the classification also relied on non-linguistic anthropological and culturally contingent features, such as skin color, hair type, and lifestyle.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Ultimately, Meinhof's classification of Hamitic proved to include languages from every presently-recognized language family within Africa.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] The first scholar to question the existence of "Hamitic languages" was Marcel Cohen in 1924, with skepticism also expressed by A.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Klingenheben and Dietrich Westermann during the 1920s and '30s.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] However, Meinhof's "Hamitic" classification remained prevalent throughout the early 20th century until it was definitively disproven by Joseph Greenberg in the 1940s, based on racial and anthropological data.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Instead, Greenberg proposed an Afroasiatic family consisting of five branches: Berber, Chadic, Cushitic, Egyptian, and Semitic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Reluctance among some scholars to recognize Chadic as a branch of Afroasiatic persisted as late as the 1980s.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] In 1969, Harold Fleming proposed that a group of languages classified by Greenberg as Cushitic were in fact their own independent "Omotic" branch—a proposal that has been widely, if not universally, accepted.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] These six branches now constitute an academic consensus on the genetic structure of the family.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Greenberg relied on his own method of mass comparison of vocabulary items rather than the comparative method of demonstrating regular sound correspondences to establish the family.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] An alternative classification, based on the pronominal and conjugation systems, was proposed by A.N.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] As of 2023, widely accepted sound correspondences between the different branches have not yet been firmly established.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Nevertheless, morphological traits attributable to the proto-language and the establishment of cognates throughout the family have confirmed its genetic validity.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] There is no consensus as to when Proto-Afroasiatic was spoken.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] The absolute latest date for when Proto-Afroasiatic could have been extant is c.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] 4000 BCE, after which the existence of the clearly distinct Egyptian and the Semitic languages is firmly attested.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] However, in all likelihood these languages began to diverge well before this hard boundary.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] The estimations offered by scholars as to when Proto-Afroasiatic was spoken vary widely, ranging from 18,000 BCE to 8,000 BCE.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] An estimate at the youngest end of this range still makes Afroasiatic the oldest proven language family.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Likewise, no consensus exists as to where proto-Afroasiatic originated.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Scholars have proposed locations for the Afroasiatic homeland across Africa and West Asia.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Roger Blench writes that the debate possesses "a strong ideological flavor", with associations between an Asian origin and "high civilization".
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] An additional complicating factor is the lack of agreement on the subgroupings of Afroasiatic (see Further subdivisions) – this makes associating archaeological evidence with the spread of Afroasiatic particularly difficult.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Nevertheless, there is a long-accepted link between the speakers of Proto-Southern Cushitic languages and the East African Savanna Pastoral Neolithic (5,000 years ago), and archaeological evidence associates the Proto-Cushitic speakers with economic transformations in the Sahara dating c.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] 8,500 years ago, as well as the speakers of the Proto-Zenati variety of the Berber languages with an expansion across the Maghreb in the 5th century CE.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] An origin somewhere on the African continent has broad scholarly support, and is seen as being well-supported by the linguistic data.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Most scholars more narrowly place the homeland near the geographic center of its present distribution, "in the southeastern Sahara or adjacent Horn of Africa".
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] The Afroasiatic languages spoken in Africa are not more closely related to each other than they are to Semitic, as one would expect if only Semitic had remained in a West Asian homeland while all other branches had spread from there.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Likewise, all Semitic languages are fairly similar to each other, whereas the African branches of Afroasiatic are very diverse; this suggests the rapid spread of Semitic out of Africa.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Proponents of an origin of Afroasiatic within Africa assume the proto-language to have been spoken by pre-Neolithic hunter-gatherers, arguing that there is no evidence of words in Proto-Afroasiatic related to agriculture or animal husbandry.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Keita, and Paul Newman also argue that archaeology does not support a spread of migrating farmers into Africa, but rather a gradual incorporation of animal husbandry into indigenous foraging cultures.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Ehret, in a separate publication, argued that the two principles in linguistic approaches for determining the origin of languages which are the principles of fewest moves and greatest diversity had put "beyond reasonable doubt" that the language family "had originated in the Horn of Africa".
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] A significant minority of scholars supports an Asian origin of Afroasiatic, most of whom are specialists in Semitic or Egyptian studies.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] The main proponent of an Asian origin is the linguist Alexander Militarev, who argues that Proto-Afroasiatic was spoken by early agriculturalists in the Levant and subsequently spread to Africa.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Militarev associates the speakers of Proto-Afroasiatic with the Levantine Post-Natufian Culture, arguing that the reconstructed lexicon of flora and fauna, as well as farming and pastoralist vocabulary indicates that Proto-AA must have been spoken in this area.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Afroasiatic languages share a number of phonetic and phonological features.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Egyptian, Cushitic, Berber, Omotic, and most languages in the Semitic branch require every syllable to begin with a consonant (with the exception of some grammatical prefixes).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Igor Diakonoff argues that this constraint goes back to Proto-Afroasiatic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Some Chadic languages allow a syllable to begin with a vowel; however, in many Chadic languages verbs must begin with a consonant.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] In Cushitic and Chadic languages, a glottal stop or glottal fricative may be inserted to prevent a word from beginning with a vowel.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Typically, syllables begin with only a single consonant.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Diakonoff argues that proto-Afroasiatic did not have consonant clusters within a syllable.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] With the exception of some Chadic languages, all Afroasiatic languages allow both open syllables (ending in a vowel) and closed syllables (ending in a consonant); many Chadic languages do not allow a syllable to end in a consonant.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Most words end in a vowel in Omotic and Cushitic, making syllable-final consonant clusters rare.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Syllable weight plays an important role in Afroasiatic, especially in Chadic; it can affect the form of affixes attached to a word.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Several Afroasiatic languages have large consonant inventories, and it is likely that this is inherited from proto-Afroasiatic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] All Afroasiatic languages contain stops and fricatives; some branches have additional types of consonants such as affricates and lateral consonants.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Afroasiatic languages tend to have pharyngeal fricative consonants, with Egyptian, Semitic, Berber, and Cushitic sharing ħ and ʕ.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] In all Afroasiatic languages, consonants can be bilabial, alveolar, velar, and glottal, with additional places of articulation found in some branches or languages.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Additionally, the glottal stop (ʔ) usually exists as a phoneme, and there tends to be no phonemic contrast between [p] and [f] or [b] and [v].
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] In Cushitic, the Ethiopian Semitic language Tigrinya, and some Chadic languages, there is no underlying phoneme [p] at all.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Most, if not all branches of Afroasiatic distinguish between voiceless, voiced, and "emphatic" consonants.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] The emphatic consonants are typically formed deeper in the throat than the others; they can be realized variously as glottalized, pharyngealized, uvularized, ejective, and/or implosive consonants in the different branches.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] This distinction between three manners of articulation is not generally reconstructed for continuant obstruents (such as fricatives), which are generally reconstructed as being only voiceless in Proto-Afroasiatic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] A form of long-distance consonant assimilation known as consonant harmony is attested in Berber, Chadic, Cushitic, and Semitic: it usually affects features such as pharyngealization, palatalization, and labialization.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Several Omotic languages have "sibilant harmony", meaning that all sibilants (s, sh, z, ts, etc.) in a word must match.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Restrictions against the co-occurrence of certain, usually similar, consonants in verbal roots can be found in all Afroasiatic branches, though they are only weakly attested in Chadic and Omotic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] The most widespread constraint is against two different labial consonants (other than *w*) occurring together in a root, a constraint which can be found in all branches but Omotic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Another widespread constraint is against two non-identical lateral obstruents, which can be found in Egyptian, Chadic, Semitic, and probably Cushitic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Such rules do not always apply for nouns, numerals, or denominal verbs, and do not affect prefixes or suffixes added to the root.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Roots that may have contained sequences that were possible in Proto-Afroasiatic but are disallowed in the daughter languages are assumed to have undergone consonant dissimilation or assimilation.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] A set of constraints, developed originally by Joseph Greenberg on the basis of Arabic, has been claimed to be typical for Afroasiatic languages.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Greenberg divided Semitic consonants into four types: "back consonants" (glottal, pharyngeal, uvular, laryngeal, and velar consonants), "front consonants" (dental or alveolar consonants), liquid consonants, and labial consonants.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] He showed that, generally, any consonant from one of these groups could combine with consonants from any other group, but could not be used together with consonants from the same group.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Additionally, he showed that Proto-Semitic restricted a sequence of two identical consonants in the first and second position of the triliteral root.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] 2. dental consonants can co-occur with sibilants; However, there are no Proto-Semitic verbal roots with *ḍ* and a sibilant, and roots with *d* and a sibilant are uncommon.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] In all attested cases of a dental and a sibilant, the sibilant occurs in first position and the dental in second.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Similar exceptions can be demonstrated for the other Afroasiatic branches that have these restrictions to their root formation.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Allen has demonstrated that slightly different rules apply to Egyptian: for instance, Egyptian allows two identical consonants in some roots, and disallows velars from occurring with pharyngeals.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] There is a large variety of vocalic systems in Afroasiatic, and attempts to reconstruct the vocalic system of Proto-Afroasiatic vary considerably.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] All branches of Afroasiatic have a limited number of underlying vowels (between two and seven), but the number of phonetic vowels can be much larger.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] The quality of the underlying vowels varies considerably by language; the most common vowel throughout Afroasiatic is schwa.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] In the different languages, central vowels are often inserted to break up consonant clusters (a form of epenthesis).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Various Semitic, Cushitic, Berber, and Chadic languages, including Arabic, Amharic, Berber, Somali, and East Dangla, also exhibit various types of vowel harmony.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] The majority of Afroasiatic languages are tonal languages: phonemic tonality is found in Omotic, Chadic, and Cushitic languages, but absent in Berber and Semitic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] There is no information on whether Egyptian had tones.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] In contemporary Omotic, Chadic, and Cushitic languages, tone is primarily a grammatical feature: it encodes various grammatical functions, only differentiating lexical roots in a few cases.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] In some Chadic and some Omotic languages every syllable has to have a tone, whereas in most Cushitic languages this is not the case.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p01] Some scholars postulate that Proto-Afroasiatic may have had tone, while others believe it arose later from a pitch accent.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] At present, there is no generally accepted reconstruction of Proto-Afroasiatic grammar, syntax, or morphology, nor one for any of the sub-branches besides Egyptian.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] This means that it is difficult to know which features in Afroasiatic languages are retentions, and which are innovations.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Moreover, all Afroasiatic languages have long been in contact with other language families and with each other, leading to the possibility of widespread borrowing both within Afroasiatic and from unrelated languages.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] There are nevertheless a number of commonly observed features in Afroasiatic morphology and derivation, including the use of suffixes, infixes, vowel lengthening and shortening as a morphological change, as well as the use of tone changes to indicate morphology.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Further commonalities and differences are explored in more detail below.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] A widely attested feature in AA languages is a consonantal structure into which various vocalic "templates" are placed.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] This structure is particularly visible in the verbs, and is particularly noticeable in Semitic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Besides for Semitic, vocalic templates are well attested for Cushitic and Berber, where, along with Chadic, it is less productive; it is absent in Omotic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] For Egyptian, evidence for the root-and-template structure exists from Coptic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] In Semitic, Egyptian, Berber, verbs have no inherent vowels at all; the vowels found in a given stem are dependent on the vocalic template.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] In Chadic, verb stems can include an inherent vowel as well.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Most Semitic verbs are triliteral (have three consonants), whereas most Chadic, Omotic, and Cushitic verbs are biliteral (having two consonants).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] The degree to which the Proto-AA verbal root was triliteral is debated.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] It may have originally been mostly biconsonantal, to which various affixes (such as verbal extensions) were then added and lexicalized.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Although any root could theoretically be used to create a noun or a verb, there is evidence for the existence of distinct noun and verb roots, which behave in different ways.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] As part of these templates, the alternation (apophony) between high vowels (e.g. i, u) and a low vowel (a) in verbal forms is usually described as one of the main characteristics of AA languages: this change codes a variety of different functions.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] It is unclear whether this system is a common AA trait; the Chadic examples, for instance, show signs of originally deriving from affixes, which could explain the origins of the alterations in other languages as well.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] It remains unclear what word order Proto-Afroasiatic had.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Berber, Egyptian, and most Semitic languages are verb-initial languages, whereas Cushitic, Omotic and some Semitic subgroups are verb-final languages.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Proto-Chadic is reconstructed as having verb-initial word order, but most Chadic languages have subject-verb-object word order.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Afroasiatic Languages use the processes of reduplication and gemination (which often overlap in meaning) to derive nouns, verbs, adjectives, and adverbs throughout the AA language family.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Gemination in particular is one of the typical features of AA.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Full or partial reduplication of the verb is often used to derive forms showing repeated action (pluractionality), though it is unclear if this is an inherited feature or has been widely borrowed.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] The assignment of nouns and pronouns to either masculine or feminine gender is present in all branches – but not all languages – of the Afroasiatic family.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] This sex-based gender system is widely agreed to derive from Proto-Afroasiatic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] In most branches, gender is an inherent property of nouns.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Additionally, even when nouns are not cognates, they tend to have the same gender throughout Afroasiatic ("gender stability").
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] In Egyptian, Semitic, and Berber, a feminine suffix -t is attested to mark feminine nouns; in some Cushitic and Chadic languages, a feminine -t suffix or prefix (lexicalized from a demonstrative) is used to mark definiteness.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] In addition to these uses, -t also functions as a diminutive, pejorative, and/or singulative marker in some languages.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Afroasiatic languages have a variety of ways of marking plurals; in some branches, nouns change gender from singular to plural (gender polarity), while in others, plural forms are ungendered.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] In addition to marking plurals via a number of affixes (with the suffixes -*uu/-*w and -*n(a) widely attested), several AA languages make use of internal vowel change (apophony) and/or insertion (epenthesis).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] These so-called "internal-a" or "broken" plurals are securely attested in Semitic, Berber, Cushitic, and Chadic, although it is unclear if the Chadic examples are an independent development.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Another common method of forming plurals is reduplication.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Nouns cases are found in the Semitic, Berber, Cushitic, and Omotic branches.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] They are not found in Chadic languages, and there is no evidence for cases in Egyptian.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] A common pattern in AA languages with case is for the nominative to be marked by *-u* or *-i*, and the accusative to be marked by *-a*.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] However, the number and types of cases varies across AA and also within the individual branches.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Some languages in AA have a marked nominative alignment, a feature which may date back to Proto-Afroasiatic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Zygmont Frajzyngier states that a general characteristic of case marking in AA languages is that it tends to mark roles such as genitive, dative, locative, etc. rather than the subject and object.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] A second category, which partially overlaps with case, is the AA linguistic category of "state".
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Linguists use the term "state" to refer to different things in different languages.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] In Cushitic and Semitic, nouns exist in the "free state" or the "construct state".
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] The construct state is a special, usually reduced form of a noun, which is used when the noun is possessed by another noun (Semitic) or is modified by an adjective or relative clause (Cushitic).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Edward Lipiński refers to Semitic nouns as having four states: absolute (free/indeterminate), construct, determinate, and predicate.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Coptic and Egyptian grammar also refers to nouns having a "free" (absolute) state, a "construct state", and a "pronominal state".
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] The construct state is used when a noun becomes unstressed as the first element of a compound, whereas the pronominal state is used when the noun has a suffixed possessive pronoun.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Berber instead contrasts between the "free state" and the "annexed state", the latter of which is used for a variety of purposes, including for subjects placed after a verb and after certain prepositions.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] There is no strict distinction between adjectives, nouns, and adverbs in Afroasiatic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] All branches of Afroasiatic have a lexical category of adjectives except for Chadic; some Chadic languages do have adjectives, however.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] In Berber languages, adjectives are rare and are mostly replaced by nouns of quality and stative verbs.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] In different languages, adjectives (and other modifiers) must either precede or follow the noun.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] In most AA languages, numerals precede the noun.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] In those languages that have adjectives, they can take gender and number markings, which, in some cases, agree with the gender and number of the noun they are modifying.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] However, in Omotic, adjectives do not agree with nouns: sometimes, they take gender and number marking only when they are used as nouns, in other cases, they take gender and number marking only when they follow the noun (the noun then receives no marking).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] A widespread pattern of gender and number marking in Afroasiatic, found on demonstratives, articles, adjectives, and relative markers, is a consonant N for masculine, T for feminine, and N for plural.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] This can be found in Semitic, Egyptian, Beja, Berber, and Chadic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] A system K (masculine), T (feminine), and H (plural) can be found in Cushitic, Chadic, with masculine K also appearing in Omotic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] The feminine marker T is one of the most consistent aspects across the different branches of AA.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] There is no agreement about which tenses, aspects, or moods (TAMs) Proto-Afroasiatic might have had.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Most grammars of AA posit a distinction between perfective and imperfective verbal aspects, which can be found in Cushitic, Berber, Semitic, most Chadic languages, and some Omotic languages.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] The Egyptian verbal system diverges greatly from that found in the other branches.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Additionally, it is common in Afroasiatic languages for the present/imperfective form to be a derived (marked) form of the verb, whereas in most other languages and language families the present tense is the default form of the verb.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Another common trait across the family is the use of a suppletive imperative for verbs of motion.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Conjugation of verbs using prefixes that mark person, number, and gender can be found in Semitic, Berber, and in Cushitic, where it is only found on a small set of frequent verbs.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] These prefixes are clearly cognate across the branches, although their use within the verbal systems of the individual languages varies.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] There is a general pattern in which n- is used for the first person plural, whereas t- is used for all forms of the second person regardless of plurality or gender, as well as feminine singular.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Prefixes of ʔ- (glottal stop) for the first person singular and y- for the third person masculine can also be reconstructed.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] As there is no evidence for the "prefix conjugation" in Omotic, Chadic, or Egyptian, it is unclear whether this was a Proto-Afroasiatic feature that has been lost in those branches or is a shared innovation among Semitic, Berber, and Cushitic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Some AA branches have what is called a "suffix conjugation", formed by adding pronominal suffixes to indicate person, gender, and number to a verbal adjective.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] In Akkadian, Egyptian, Berber, and Cushitic this forms a "stative conjugation", used to express the state or result of an action; the same endings as in Akkadian and Egyptian are also present in the West Semitic perfective verb form.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] In Akkadian and Egyptian, the suffixes appear to be reduced forms of the independent pronouns (see Pronouns); the obvious correspondence between the endings in the two branches has been argued to show that Egyptian and Semitic are closely related.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] While some scholars posit an AA origin for this form, it is possible that the Berber and Cushitic forms are independent developments, as they show significant differences from the Egyptian and Semitic forms.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] The Cushitic forms in particular may be derived from morphology found in subordinate clauses.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] A prefix in m- is the most widely attested affix in AA that is used to derive nouns, and is one of the features Joseph Greenberg used to diagnose membership in the family.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] It forms agent nouns, place nouns, and instrument nouns.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] In some branches, it can also derive abstract nouns and participles.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Omotic, meanwhile, shows evidence for a non-productive prefix mV- associated with the feminine gender.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Christopher Ehret has argued that this prefix is a later development that was not present in Proto-Afro-Asiatic, but rather derived from a PAA indefinite pronoun *m-.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Zaborski and Gábor Takács, the latter of whom argues for a PAA **ma-* that unites all or some of the meanings in the modern languages.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Many AA languages use prefixes or suffixes (verbal extensions) to encode various pieces of information about the verb.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Three derivational prefixes can be reconstructed for Proto-Afroasiatic: *s- 'causative', *t- 'middle voice' or 'reflexive', and *n- 'passive'; the prefixes appear with various related meanings in the individual daughter languages and branches.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Christopher Ehret has proposed that Proto-Afroasiatic originally had as many as thirty-seven separate verbal extensions, many of which then became fossilized as third consonants.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] This theory has been criticized by some, such as Andrzej Zaborski and Alan Kaye, as being too many extensions to be realistic, though Zygmunt Frajzyngier and Erin Shay note that some Chadic languages have as many as twelve extensions.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] The so-called "Nisba" is a suffix used to derive adjectives from nouns and, in Egyptian, also from prepositions.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] It is found in Egyptian, Semitic, and possibly, in some relic forms, Berber.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] The suffix has the same basic form in Egyptian and Semitic, taking the form -i(y) in Semitic and being written -j in Egyptian.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] The Semitic and Cushitic genitive case in -i/-ii may be related to "nisba" adjective derivation.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Due to its presence in the oldest attested and best-known AA branches, nisba derivation is often thought of as a "quintessentially Afroasiatic feature".
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Christopher Ehret argues for its presence in Proto-Afroasiatic and for its attestation in some form in all branches, with a shape *-*ay* in addition to -**iy* in some cases.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] The forms of the pronouns are very stable throughout Afroasiatic (excluding Omotic), and they have been used as one of the chief tools for determining whether a language belongs to the family.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] However, there is no consensus on what the reconstructed set of Afroasiatic pronouns might have looked like.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] A common characteristic of AA languages is the existence of a special set of "independent" pronouns, which are distinct from subject pronouns.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] They can occur together with subject pronouns but cannot fulfill an object function.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Also common are dependent/affix pronouns (used for direct objects and to mark possession).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] For most branches, the first person pronouns contain a nasal consonant (n, m), whereas the third person displays a sibilant consonant (s, sh).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Other commonalities are masculine and feminine forms used in both the second and third persons, except in Cushitic and Omotic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] These pronouns tend to show a masculine "u" and a feminine "i".
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] The Omotic forms of the personal pronouns differ from the others, with only the plural forms in North Omotic appearing potentially to be cognate.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Unlike in the Indo-European or Austronesian language families, numerals in AA languages cannot be traced to a proto-system.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] The Cushitic and Chadic numeral systems appear to have originally been base 5.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] The system in Berber, Egyptian, and Semitic, however, has independent words for the numbers 6–9.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Thus, it is possible that the numerals in Egyptian, Berber, and Semitic are more closely related, whereas the Cushitic and Chadic numerals are more closely related to each other.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Modern Chadic numeral systems are sometimes decimal, having separate names for the numbers 1–10, and sometimes base-5, deriving the numbers 6–9 from the numbers 1–5 in some way.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Some families show more than one word for a numeral: Chadic, Semitic, and Berber each have two words for two, and Semitic has four words for one.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Andrzej Zaborski further notes that the numbers "one", "two", and "five" are particularly susceptible to replacement by new words, with "five" often based on a word meaning "hand".
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Another factor making comparisons of AA numeral systems difficult is the possibility of borrowing.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Only some Berber languages maintain the native Berber numeral system, with many using Arabic loans for higher numbers and some from any numeral beyond two.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] In some Berber languages, the roots for one and two are also borrowed from Arabic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Some South Cushitic numerals are borrowed from Nilotic languages, other Cushitic numerals have been borrowed from Ethiopian Semitic languages.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Afroasiatic languages share a vocabulary of Proto-Afroasiatic origin to varying extents.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Writing in 2004, John Huehnergard notes the great difficulty in establishing cognate sets across the family.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Identifying cognates is difficult because the languages in question are often separated by thousands of years of development and many languages within the family have long been in contact with each other, raising the possibility of loanwords.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Work is also hampered because of the poor state of documentation of many languages.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] There are two etymological dictionaries of Afroasiatic, one by Christopher Ehret, and one by Vladimir Orel and Olga Stolbova, both from 1995.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Both works provide highly divergent reconstructions and have been heavily criticized by other scholars.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Andrzej Zaborski refers to Orel and Stolbova's reconstructions as "controversial", and Ehret's as "not acceptable to many scholars".
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Tom Güldemann argues that much comparative work in Afroasiatic suffers from not attempting first to reconstruct smaller units within the individual branches, but instead comparing words in the individual languages.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Nevertheless, both dictionaries agree on some items and some proposed cognates are uncontroversial.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/afroasiatic-languages-p02] Such cognates tend to rely on relatively simple sound correspondences.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] The **Azerbaijani alphabet** is used to write Azerbaijani.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] There are three different scripts commonly used for writing Azerbaijani: the Arabic, Latin, and Cyrillic alphabets.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] North Azerbaijani, the most common dialect spoken in the Republic of Azerbaijan, is written in the Latin script.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] After the fall of the Soviet Union, the Latin alphabet superseded previous scripts based on the Cyrillic and Arabic scripts.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] South Azerbaijani, the language spoken in Iran's Azerbaijan region, has been written in a modified Arabic script since the Safavid Empire.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] In the Dagestan region, Azerbaijani is still commonly written in the Cyrillic script.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] The Azerbaijani Latin alphabet consists of 32 letters.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] From the nineteenth century, intellectuals like Mirza Fatali Akhundov and Mammad agha Shahtakhtinski attempted to replace Arabic script with a Latin alphabet for Azerbaijani.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] Akhundov argued that the Arabic alphabet's structure made literacy difficult for the general population and kept education under a small elite.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] Akhundov's views on alphabet reform developed over about twenty years.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] Initially, he proposed keeping the Arabic alphabet’s basic structure, removing dots, and adding marks for unwritten vowels.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] Next, he suggested letters be written separately, each with a distinct form.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] Finally, he recommended a Latin-based alphabet, written left to right, clearly representing all vowels.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] Akhundzade promoted his **“New Alphabet Project”** in political and intellectual centers.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] In 1863, he presented it in Istanbul to Fuad Pasha and Ali Pasha, and it was discussed at the Cemiyyet-i İlmiyye-i Osmaniyye.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] Although the Arabic alphabet's defects were acknowledged, Akhundzade's project received no official support due to technical printing difficulties and political conditions.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] From 1857, he also submitted proposals to Iranian authorities, but they were not officially accepted.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] In 1922, a Latin alphabet was created by the USSR-sponsored *Yeni türk əlifba komitəsi* (New Turkic Alphabet Committee; Јени түрк əлифба комитəси) in Baku.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] This committee hoped that the new alphabet would divide the Azerbaijanis in the USSR from those living in Iran.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] The Soviet Union also hoped that a Latin alphabet would help secularize Azerbaijan's Muslim culture.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] There was some historical basis for the reform, which received overwhelming support at the First Turkology Congress in Baku during 1926, where the reform was voted by 101 to 7.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] The Azerbaijani poet Samad Vurgun declared, "Azerbaijani people are proud of being the first among Oriental nations that buried the Arabic alphabet and adopted the Latin alphabet.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] This event is written in golden letters of our history".
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] From 1922 to 1929, both Arabic and Latin scripts were used in Soviet texts printed in Azerbaijan; in 1929, the Latin script officially replaced the Arabic script.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] In 1933, the Azerbaijani Latin alphabet was reformed to match the alphabets of other Soviet Turkic languages (see Yañalif, Uniform Turkic Alphabet).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] The reform changed certain glyphs and certain letters' phonetic values.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] In 1939 Joseph Stalin ordered the discontinuation of the Azerbaijani Latin script, and ordered that Azerbaijani be written in Cyrillic script, to sever the Soviet Azerbaijani Turks' ties with the Turkish people in the Republic of Turkey.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] When the Soviet Union collapsed in 1991 and Azerbaijan gained its independence, one of the first laws passed in the new Parliament was the adoption of a new Latin-script alphabet.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] From 1991 to 2001, there was a transitional period, when both Latin and Cyrillic alphabets were accepted.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] Since 2001, the Azerbaijani Latin alphabet has been the official alphabet of the Azerbaijani language in the Republic of Azerbaijan.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] The Azerbaijani alphabet is the same as the Turkish alphabet, except for **Әə**, **Xx**, and **Qq**, which do not exist as separate phonemes in Turkish.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] There are several important changes between the modern Latin Azerbaijani alphabet and its predecessors.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] The sounds [k] and [ɡ] in loanwords were rendered respectively as **q** and **ƣ** in the Latin alphabet of 1933, but as **к** and **г** in Cyrillic and are rendered as **k** and **q** in the current Latin alphabet: *ƣrafiqa* (1933 Latin) — графика (Cyrillic) — *qrafika* (current Latin).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] In translingual contexts (e.g. mathematics), the letters of the ISO basic Latin alphabet are named in Azerbaijani in the following way: *a, be, ce (se), de, e, ef, qe, aş (haş), i, yot, ka, el, em, en, o, pe, ku, er, es, te, u, ve, dubl-ve, iks, iqrek, zet*.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] When the new Latin script was introduced on 25 December 1991, A-diaeresis (*Ä ä*) was selected to represent the sound /æ/.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] However, on 16 May 1992, it was replaced by the previously-used grapheme schwa (*Ə ə*).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] Although use of *Ä ä* (also used in Tatar, Turkmen, and Gagauz) seems to be a simpler alternative, as the schwa is absent in most character sets, it was reintroduced for historical reasons.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] The schwa had historically represented Azerbaijani's most common vowel in both post-Arabic alphabets (Latin and Cyrillic) of Azerbaijan.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] However, the "upside-down 'e'" on computers caused considerable problems during the early 1990s, as its placement on standard Azerbaijani keyboards and its assignment in computer encodings had not yet become standardized.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] The development of a standardized orthography for Azerbaijani using the Arabic script in Iran began in late 20th century.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] Historically, the Persian alphabet has been used for Azerbaijani; however, linguists associated with the standardization movement, such as those contributing to the journal Varlıq (est.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] 1979), argue that the unmodified Persian system presents phonetic redundancies.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] For example, the Persian script contains multiple letters for the same consonant sounds—such as the letters ت and ط for the voiceless alveolar plosive [t], and lacks dedicated characters or diacritics for several vowel phonemes specific to Turkic languages.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] Efforts to formalize these conventions culminated in a series of linguistic seminars held in Tehran in 2001.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] Chaired by Javad Heyat, the founder of *Varlıq*, these sessions produced a document outlining a standardized orthography for the public.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] This system was subsequently integrated into the *Lügatnâme-ye Torki-ye Âzarbâyjâni* (Azerbaijani Turkic Dictionary).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] While the Arabic-based script remains the most widespread medium for the language in Iran, its usage patterns have shifted in the 21st century.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] Although Article 15 of the Iranian Constitution provides for the use of regional and tribal languages in the press and mass media, as well as the teaching of their literature in schools, a formal state-wide curriculum for Azerbaijani has not been fully implemented.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] In recent decades, the adoption of the Latin alphabet has increased among younger speakers.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] This trend is often attributed to the influence of the Latin-based script used in the Republic of Azerbaijan and the technical convenience of Latin-based keyboard layouts on digital platforms and mobile devices.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] In the Azerbaijani Arabic alphabet, nine vowels are defined.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] Six of those vowels are present in Persian, whereas three are missing.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] Diacritics (including hamza) in combination with the letters *alef* (ا), *vav* (و) or *ye* (ی) are used to mark each of these vowels.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] Important to note that similar to Persian alphabet, vowels in the initial position require an *alef* (ا) all the time—and if needed, followed by either *vav* (و) or *ye* (ی).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] This excludes Arabic loanwords that may start with *ʿayn* (ع).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] Like other Turkic languages, Azerbaijani has a system of vowel harmony.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] Azerbaijani's system of vowel harmony is primarily a front/back system.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] This means that all vowels in a word must be ones that are pronounced either at the front or at the back of the mouth.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] In Azerbaijani there are two suffixes that make a plural.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] It is either -ـلَر *-lər* or -ـلار *-lar*, front and back vowels respectively.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] The same variety of options for suffixes exists across the board in Azerbaijani.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] A secondary vowel harmony system exists in Azerbaijani language, which is a rounded/unrounded system.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] This applies to some (but not all) of the suffixes.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] For example, there are four variations for the common suffix لی- *-lı/-li* and -لو *-lu/-lü*.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] In the Perso-Arabic script, or in Arabic scripts in general, diacritics are usually not written out, except in texts for beginners or to avoid confusion with a similarly written word.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] In the Azerbaijani Arabic alphabet, there are conventions with regards to writing of diacritics.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] For *A-a* (آ / ‍ـا), the vowel is always written and shown with *alef*.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] For *Ə-ə* (اَ / ـَ / ـه‌ / ه), the initial vowel is written with an *alef*.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] Vowels in the middle of the word are written in two ways.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] They are either shown, i.e. written with a diacritic, which usually needs not be written; or they are written with a final *he* (ـه‌ / ه).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] The former is used in closed syllables (CVC), or in the first open syllable of the word.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] The latter is used in open syllables (CV) with the exception of the first syllable of the word.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] Note that the vowel *he* (ـه‌ / ه) is not attached to the following letter, but is separated from it with a Zero-width non-joiner.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] For example, the word *gələcəyim* (gə-lə-cəy-im) 'my future' is written as گله‌جگیم.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] Note that the first syllable of the word is open, but it is not marked.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] The second syllable is open, and thus the vowel is marked with *he* (ـه‌ / ه), not attached to the following letter.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] Also note the breakdown of the word into syllables – this is because the word is made up of *gələcək* plus possessive pronoun *-im*.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] For E-e (ائ / ئ), the sound is shown with a *hamzeh* on top of a *ye* in almost all cases.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] The exceptions are loanwords of Persian, Arabic, or European origin.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] For example, *enerji* 'energy' is written as انرژی.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] Other examples include تلویزیون *televiziyon* 'TV'), علم *elm* 'science', and قانع *qane* 'satisfied'.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] In words, for both Azerbaijani and loanwords, if ⟨E⟩ and ⟨Y⟩ come side by side, both letters are written; e.g., قئید *qeyd*, شئیدا *şeyda*, ویئتنام *Vyetnam*, غئیرت *ğeyrət*.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] Loanwords from Persian or Arabic which contain the sound [i], but are adopted in Azerbaijani with an [e] sound, are shown with ⟨ئ⟩.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] Examples include تسبئح *təsbeh*, بئساواد *besavad*, پئشکش *peşkəş*.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] For *İ-i* (ای / ی), the sound is always shown with *ye* (ی).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] For *I-ı* (ایٛ / یٛ), the sound is shown with *ye* (ی) all the time.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] The writing of the diacritic is optional and not necessary, and is only ever actually done in beginner language lesson books or to avoid confusion with a similarly written word.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] Native speakers can usually read words without the use of diacritic, as they are aware of vowel harmony rules (meaning that they can interpolate the correct pronunciation of ⟨ی⟩ by the presence of other vowels in the word).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] In words like *qızıl* قیزیل 'gold', familiarity with the vocabulary helps native speakers.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] For round vowels, *O-o* (اوْ / وْ), *U-u* (اوُ / وُ), *Ö-ö* (اؤ / ؤ), and *Ü-ü* (اوٚ / وٚ), it is recommended that the first syllable containing such vowel be marked with diacritic, while the rest can remain unmarked and solely written with a *vav* (و).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] This reduces the effort of marking vowels, while also providing readers with a clue with respect to vowel harmony, namely as to whether the vowels of the word are to be front or back.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] Examples include گؤرونوش *görünüş*, اوْغوز *oğuz*, دوٚیون *düyün*.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] However, it is recommended new learners write diacritics on all round vowels, e.g., گؤروٚنوٚش *görünüş*, اوْغوُز *oğuz*, دوٚیوٚن *düyün*.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] In daily practice, it is rare to see vowels other than *Ö-ö* (اؤ / ؤ) marked.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] This may be because *hamza* is the only one of such symbols that is frequently written in Persian as well, and because the inverted "v" diacritic for *Ü-ü* (اوٚ / وٚ) does not exist on typical Persian keyboards.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] While Azerbaijani Latin alphabet has nine vowels and twenty-three consonants, the Azerbaijani Arabic alphabet has thirty consonants, as there are sounds that are represented by more than one consonant.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] Highlighted columns indicate letters from Persian or Arabic that are exclusively used in loanwords, and not in native Azerbaijani words.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] There is a distinction between the pronunciation of "غ" and "ق" in Azerbaijani.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] Such distinction does not exist in standard Iranian Persian.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] But in any case, loanwords from Arabic or Persian, regardless of how their "غ" and "ق" is pronounced, are to be kept as their original writing.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] An example being the word meaning *Afghan*, "افغان" (Əfqan).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] The "غ" in Azerbaijani is pronounced as a [g], meaning that, as it is done in Latin, it is being pronounced as if it is a "ق".
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] But the writing of the loanword in Azerbaijani Arabic will remain the same.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] Loanwords whose original spelling was with a "گ" (G g) but are written in Latin alphabet with a Q q, are to be written with a "ق".
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] When suffixes are added to words ending in "ک" (K k), resulting in the letter "ک" (K k) being between two vowels, will have its pronunciation modified to [j], equivalent to the letter "ی" (Y y).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] This change is reflected in Latin writing.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] However, in the Arabic script, to maintain the original familiar shape of the word, the letter "گ" (G g) (functioning in a role dubbed "soft G") is used, as the letter is similar in shape to "ک".
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] Examples: "çörə**k**+im" becoming "çörə**y**im" in Latin script *(meaning my bread)*, but "چؤر**ک**+یم" becoming "چؤر**گ**یم".
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] "gələcə**k**+im" becoming "gələcə**y**im" in Latin script *(meaning my future)*, but "گله‌ج**ک**+یم" becoming "گله‌ج**گ**یم".
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] Whenever the letter "ی" (Y) is placed between two "ای" (İ-i) vowels, it is written as "گ" (G g) (functioning in a role dubbed "soft G").
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] This is not something done in Latin script.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] The letters "و" ,"ه / هـ", and "ی" have a double function, as consonant, and as part of vowels.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] When used as consonant, they are written with no diacritic or marking.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] Shadda, the Arabic diacritic for gemination, is retained for loanwords from Arabic.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] Examples: "مۆکمّل" (mükəmməl) *(meaning complementary)*, "مدنیّت" (mədəniyyət) *(meaning civility)*.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] In native Azerbaijani words and in loanwords of European origin, double consonants are written twice.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] Examples: "یئددی" (yeddi) *(meaning seven)*, "ساققال" (saqqal) *(meaning beard)*, "اوْتللو" (Otello).
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] This section contains the national anthem of Azerbaijan, in the current Latin, Cyrillic, Jaŋalif, and Arabic alphabets.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] The Arabic, Latin, and Cyrillic alphabets each have a different sequence of letters.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] The Azerbaijani Arabic alphabet originally contained the letter ڴ.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] Originally ڴ stood for the sound [ŋ], which then merged with [n].
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] Initial versions of the Azerbaijani Latin alphabet contained the letter Ꞑꞑ, which was dropped in 1938.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] This letter no longer exists in the Azerbaijani Arabic orthographic conventions anymore either.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] The letter Цц, intended for the sound [ts] in loanwords, was used in Azerbaijani Cyrillic until 1951.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] In Azerbaijani, like in most Turkic languages, the sound [ts] generally becomes [s].
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] The apostrophe was used until 2004 in loanwords from Persian for representing the glottal stop or vowel length.
[src:azerbaijani-alphabet/azerbaijani-alphabet] Since 2004, the apostrophe is not used in Azerbaijani except in foreign proper names.
